<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genetic Variation Speeds AIDS Progression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from U.S.
National Institutes of Health have discovered that some variations
of genes said to be able to slow the progression of AIDS, actually
accelerate the disease, says a study published in the latest issue
of Science.
</P>
<P>
Researchers previously found four genes--CCR5, SDF, CCR5P and
CCR2-- could slow the progression of HIV by preventing the virus
from invading cells. But further study suggests that each of these
genes has variations that actually accelerate the disease.
</P>
<P>
They found that about 10 percent to 15 percent of all HIV
patients progress rapidly to AIDS, an advanced stage of HIV
infection. Of these people, 10 percent to 17 percent have two
copies of the CCR5P1 gene variation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. researchers hope to discover all the gene variations
involved in both the rapid acceleration of HIV and in the slow
progress of the disease, because this will help in the design
and testing of vaccines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
