<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Lifts Regulation on Currency Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Georgian government has
decided to stop intervention in currency exchange market from next
Monday to allow the rate of the national currency lari to float,
National Bank Chief Irakly Managadze said.
</P>
<P>
Georgian State Minister Vazha Lordkipanidze said Saturday that
the lari may fall to "the lowest possible level" after the
government stops regulating the rate of exchange.
</P>
<P>
He said the slump will be followed by stabilization at the
level of 2-2.5 laris per U.S. dollar from 1.4 lari per U.S. dollar
by the end of December.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian leadership carries full responsibility for the
current situation which "will most certainly be stabilized," the
State Minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
