<HEADLINE> Most Canadians Want More Private Elements in Medicare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Most Canadians believe their
country's medicare system needs substantial changes to allow for
more private elements, shows a survey by Toronto-based Pollara.
</P>
<P>
The survey interviewed more than 3,000 people, including 1,000
medicare workers and patient right advocates.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-three percent of those surveyed felt that they should be
permitted by law to dip into their own pocket for "upgraded"
treatment while 61 percent hold that the medicare's universality
should not be undermined.
</P>
<P>
Supports for larger private elements in the medicare system are
coming mainly from young adults under the age of 34, the survey
shows.
</P>
<P>
Canadians still think Canada's medicare system is the country's
defining character.
</P>
<P>
The survey finds that Canadians, while supporting the current
system, understand that they can no longer rely completely on the
government to meet all their medical needs, said Jim Saunders,
president of the Health Resources Group Inc.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
