<HEADLINE> College Education Needs Reform: Kuchma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
said Saturday that college education in the country calls for
reform to solve the shortage of funds, a problem faced by most
government-funded universities and colleges.
</P>
<P>
Students should pay for their college education and this is not
in contradiction with the principle of social fairness, Kuchma
said in his speech at a university in southeast Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma promised that the government will continue to provide
funds for college education even if the country's high-level
education completes the transition from a government monopoly to a
multi-channel funding frame.
</P>
<P>
The president also called for examing the teaching quality of
private universities and colleges.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine now has 660 universities and colleges with 520,000
students enrolled, among whom are 400,000 full-time students.
</P>
<P>
Some universities have already started to collect tuition fees
from students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
