<HEADLINE> Kyrgyz President Bans Death Penalty for Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev on
Saturday signed a decree, introducing a two-year moratorium on
executions, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The decree was announced to coincide with 50th anniversary of
the general declaration of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting marking the anniversary, Akayev said that
he approved a draft law on amnesty, which will pardon over 2,000
convicts.
</P>
<P>
"Trust and forgiveness heal the sole," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two-year ban will apply to death sentences, said a
spokesman for the presidential administration's defense and police
department.
</P>
<P>
The department did not gave the number of people who were given
a death sentence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
