<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Russia Sign New Agreement on Double Taxation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Russia signed here
Saturday a new agreement to avoid double taxation, with Cyprus
terming it as the "most important event in 1998" for its economy.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which will be valid for five years, was signed
by Cypriot Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou and
visiting Russian Vice Minister of Finance Alexei Kutrin.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement provides for a review of the taxation of
profits on dividends which will be calculated in accordance with
the 1992 agreements of the Russian Federtion with European
countries and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also lays down that there will be no taxation for
profits made from services or profits from interests.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a memorandum concerning bilateral
relations in the economic domain.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the second meeting of the Joint
Intergovernmental Committee will be held at a time in the first
six months of 1999 to discuss ways to promote commerce and trade
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the two sides reaffirmed the existence of mutual
interest to develop and strengthen cooperation in the field
of investments.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said the memorandum will decisively contribute to
the commercial and economic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kutrin expressed the Russian government's satisfaction, saying
that the 1982 agreement was reviewed in many sectors and now
it fully reflects the Russian economy's situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
