<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-05 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Cabinet Works on Policy Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The newly formed Lebanese
cabinet Saturday convened its first meeting to draft a policy
statement on the basis of which the cabinet is expected to obtain
a vote of confidence in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government under the newly-elected President Emile Lahoud
was formally announced by Prime Minister-Designate Salim Hoss
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member cabinet was made up of politicians and
technocrats, only two of whom worked in the previous government
headed by Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Hoss told a news conference that the policy his government
will adopt should be in line with Lahoud's speech at his
oath-taking ceremony in parliament last month.
</P>
<P>
The speech promised a campaign to eliminate corruption and
waste of public funds, charges faced by the former Hariri
government.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud also called for an economic austerity and
belt-tightening policy to gradually trim the ballooning budget
deficit, targeted at 42 percent of expenditures by the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
The statement will be drafted as soon as possible and be
submitted to the parliament for a confidence vote next week.
</P>
<P>
Under Lebanon's Constitution, a new government can not take
office until the parliament approves its policy statement.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts say the new team is most likely to win the
vote, and so to take office, as 95 lawmakers told the
president this week that they will support the Hoss-led
government.
</P>
<P>
In order to get the statement ready before next Saturday,
a ministerial committee charged with formulating the statement
was set up and held its first meeting on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hoss, 69, a veteran politician and economist, was designated
as prime minister Wednesday to replace Hariri who refused to
remain in office after his six-year term under the previous
President Elias Hrawi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
