<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Government Election Ends in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 5 (Xinhua) --Poll in Nigeria's local
government election, the first of a series of elections under
the military government's transition to civil rule program, ended
peacefully Saturday Afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Investigation by Xinhua reporters show that there was a much
larger turn-out of voters in Lagos than in previous elections
held under the scraped transition program of late leader General
Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
In the densely-populated Lagos Island, long queues were seen
in virtually all the polling stations with many of them being
more than 100 meters long.
</P>
<P>
Fewer stations and voters were seen in high-browed communities
on the Ikoyi and Victoria islands, but the atmosphere was
generally peaceful and orderly everywhere.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar Saturday
joined milllions of Nigerians to vote in the local government
election in capital Abuja, the News Agency of Nigeria reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking shortly before his voting, Abubakar said: "The
turnout is impressive and from what I have seen so far, the
elections will be successful."
</P>
<P>
The head of state reiterated his appeal to politicians to make
a success of the teransition program by playing the game
according to the rules.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar had earlier gone round some polling centers in the
capital and expressed happiness at the turnout in all the areas
visited.
</P>
<P>
Observers blieve that the high turn-out is a reflection of
confidence in the new democratization program of General
Abubakar, who has won wide support both at home and abroad for
his bold national reconciliation efforts
</P>
<P>
A middle-aged businessman said that Abubakar has done more in
his six months in power than what the previous leaders had done
in a 10 years time.
</P>
<P>
The Lagos City has been very quiet during the voting time from
early morning to 2:30 pm, as the authorities have imposed a
traffic ban.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election will produce 774 local government chairmen
from 6,996 chairmanship candidates and 8,870 councilors from
79,830 councillorship candidates.
</P>
<P>
According to the Independent Electoral Commission (INEC), a
total of 355,077 officials were employed to work at the 111,430
polling stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
INEC also said that it distributed 60 million voters' cards
during the voters' registration exercise in October.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election will determine the fate of the country's
nine temporarily registered political parties, as the INEC said
only those securing five percent of the total votes cast in each
of at least 24 out of the 36 states and Federal Capital Territy
will be finally registered.
</P>
<P>
Only those parties qualified to be finally registered in the
local government election will be allowed to contend for the
state governors legislators' elections in next January and the
presidential election in February.
</P>
<P>
A civilian goverment, the first since 1983, will take over
from the military government on May 29, 1999, according to
Nigeria's transition program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
