<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Suffering from pneumonia Russian
President Boris Yeltsin is ready to resume work in the Kremlin at
any time, Presidential press secretary Dmitry Yakushkin said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Ekho Moskvy radio station broadcast
live on Saturday, Yakushkin said that he had seen the president at
the Central Clinical Hospital where he is undergoing treatment.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is receiving a lot of documents and monitoring the
press for reports about the situation in the country and abroad.
He studies "a whole file of newspapers" daily, Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
The president does not think about his early resignation, the
spokesman said, adding that the head of state "is watching very
closely sharp or insulting statements concerning his actions made
by some politicians."
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin noted that Yeltsin is in full control of Russia's
nuclear policy. The small nuclear device is in his hands.
</P>
<P>
He also said that there is no question of lifting the
moratorium on death penalty in Russia, citing that many countries
are now considering banning or introducing death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
