<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Mission Accused of Not Being Neutral in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Somali main faction leaders
Ali Mahdi Mohamed and Hussein Mohamed Aidid Saturday accused an
international mission of not being neutral in Somalia's political
affairs.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference in south Mogadishu late Saturday
afternoon, the two co-chairmen of the disputed Mogadishu
Administration ordered the international fact finding mission not
to come to Somali capital after they failed to meet the security
arrangements of the administration.
</P>
<P>
The delegation has been touring Somalia in the past five days.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of 23 members from the regional and
international organizations including the Arab League and the
United Nations, and Egyptian and Italian ambassadors to Somalia
Saturday landed at El-Ahmed airstrip of Merca town, 100
kilometers south of Mogadishu, instead of landing in the capital
as previously scheduled.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, the faction leaders have ordered the
delegation to leave Merca town as soon as possible, claiming that
it has humiliated the Mogadishu administration by refusing the
reception arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi Mohamed accused the head of the delegation, an Ethiopian
national called Immanuel (only first name available), of
misguiding his team allegedly for the sole purpose of creating
mistrust among the Mogadishu's administration and the
international community.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was reportedly seeking the possible ways of
ending the long-standing political crisis in Somalia by
consulting the rival politicians, businessmen and the rival
traditional leaders in the war-torn African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
