<HEADLINE> Ugandan First Lady Calls for More Schools for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan First Lady Janet
Museveni has called on the government to put up more specialized
schools for the deaf and urged parents with deaf children to let
them go to school like all other children.
</P>
<P>
She made the call when speaking at a function here Saturday to
mark the silver jubilee celebrations of the Uganda National
Association for the Deaf (UNAD), according to a press release
from the President's Office.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the presidential office said the
first lady was glad that deaf people have registered for
Universal Primary Education and commended the UNAD for this
achievement. She said Uganda is the first country in the world
to have sign language in its national constitution.
</P>
<P>
The UNAD has become a crucial voice for the hitherto voiceless
section of the society and this has enabled government and other
associations to help deaf people more effectively, she asserted.
</P>
<P>
The UNAD was also hailed for uiting its members and their
families by forming branches in all regions of Uganda as well as
playing the significant role of changing the attitude of society
at large towards the deaf through various programs.
</P>
<P>
Alex Ndeezi, the UNAD chairman, said the his organization has
gone a long way to ensure the rights of people with disabilities
and that there is still need for more cooperation from the
society so that people with disabilities get total recognition
and respect.
</P>
<P>
The function was attended by ministers, MPs and a delegation
from the Danish Deaf Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
