<HEADLINE> Western Desert Key to Egypt's Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdi
el-Banbi said on Saturday that the oil and gas fields in Egypt's
Western Desert are playing a key role in the country's energy
production.
</P>
<P>
Oil production in the Western Desert stands at 130,000 barrels
a day, accounting for about 16 percent of Egypt's total oil
production a day, el-Banbi said at the end of a visit to the area.
</P>
<P>
The gas fields in the area produce 400 million cubic meters a
day, an amount which accounts for 30 percent of the total gas
production each day in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the high production of oil and gas in
the Western Desert to intensified prospection. He said oil
prospection has so far covered 50 percent of the Western Desert,
which accounts for about half of Egypt's area of 1 million square
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has a proven oil reserve of 2.9 billion barrels and
produces 830,000 barrels a day. Its oil prospection and production
is mainly carried out in the Western Desert, the Gulf of Suez, the
Nile Delta and the Mediterranean Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
