<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Comprehensive Nuclear Disarmament Is  No Easy Task  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly session Friday adopted 49 resolutions on international
disarmament, first of its kind okayed by the current Assembly
session after the world was shocked to see mushroom clouds in
South Asia last May.
</P>
<P>
There are four resolutions on nuclear disarmament and a fifth
one especially targeted at the nuclear tests in South Asia,
U.N.-based diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that these resolutions, brought into being
following the five-week general debate in the First Committee, are
expected to have most direct impact on the upcoming session of the
Conference on Disarmament in Geneva, the single multilateral
disarmament negotiating forum, and preparations for the review of
the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) in
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly decided in 1995 to indefinitely extend the
NPT, and the treaty will be reviewed every five years.
</P>
<P>
During the general debate at the First Committee, a major
General Assembly body in charge of disarmament and international
security matters, delegations from various countries have been
focusing their discussion on the nuclear disarmament, described by
authoritative U.N. sources as the most concerned and divisive
issue.
</P>
<P>
Complete prohibition and thorough destruction of nuclear
weapons is the common aspiration of mankind. However, it is really
no easy task to achieve the much-cherished dream.
</P>
<P>
First, the Cold War mentality dies hard although the Cold War
is over. The nuclear tests in South Asia is just a case in point.
People are concerned that instead of dissolving with the end of
the Cold War, some military blocs and alliances established in
that era are constantly expanding and gaining strength.
</P>
<P>
A few countries, backed up by their economic and technological
superiority, are intensifying their efforts to develop
sophisticated weapons which undermine global strategic balance and
stability, and they are frequently resorting to the use or threat
of use of force in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Such practice, seen as seeking one's own security at the cost
of that of others, is detrimental to the further relaxation of
international situation, will have negative influence on
international arms control and disarmament efforts.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the United States and Russia, the two nuclear
superpowers in the world, are tending to have more reliance on
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, Washington, in a bid to maintain its so-called
leadership in the world and safeguard its overseas interests,
prefer negative security assurance to non-nuclear-weapon
countries.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Russian Duma, out of concerns over
NATO's eastward expansion, are yet to ratify the 1993 Strategic Arms
Reduction Treaty (START II).
</P>
<P>
Against such a backdrop, Washington and Moscow have long failed
to implement their existing bilateral agreements on nuclear
disarmament at an early date, and further drastically reduce their
nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, it will not only impose positive impact on
international peace and security, but also create favorable
conditions for other nuclear-weapon states to participate in the
nuclear disarmament process as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, some country, in disregard of the strong opposition of
the international community, used the slow progress in nuclear
disarmament as an excuse to conduct nuclear tests in an attempt to
gain regional hegemony and the so-called big power status.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear tests by India in May this year were nothing but an
outrageous contempt for and a heavy blow to the widely supported
international nuclear non-proliferation regime.
</P>
<P>
Last but not least, there is a wide gap between the developing
world and Western nuclear-weapon countries in the field of nuclear
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The Non-aligned Movement (NAM) countries called for full and
thorough nuclear disarmament and the early convocation of the
Fourth Special Session on Disarmament (SSOD IV). Due to strong
opposition from the United States, the SSOD IV now turns out to be
a remote thing.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report to the 54rd General Assembly session in
last September, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that
disarmament comes between peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Now that the international situation is moving toward
relaxation, a country should channel its limited resources to
economic and social development, so as to benefit its own people
and at the same time, provide guarantee for national security and
that of the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Apart from formulating treaties, the work of international arms
control and disarmament also includes pains-taking efforts to
carry out treaties. In short, implementation is not only part and
parcel of this work, but also its ultimate objective.
</P>
<P>
It is noted with regret that some treaties are still far from
being universal, and that while having acceded to the treaties,
certain big powers are using various excuses to evade their treaty
obligations. This, in reality, has seriously compromised the
effect of the treaties.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the international community should attach great
importance to and strive to overcome difficulties and facilitate
the implementation of existing international arms control and
disarmament treaties so that they will be able to play their due
role in promoting the process of international arms control and
disarmament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
