<HEADLINE> Lebanese Fisherman Wounded by Israeli Warship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese fisherman was
wounded Saturday in an attack by an Israeli warship off Lebanon's
southern coast.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Sukmani, 26, received an injury in his right hand when
his fishing boat "Faatima" was hit by heavy shots fired from an
Israeli warship near the coastal city of Tyre, about 70 kilometers
south of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, Sukmani was rushed to a hospital in
the city for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli attack was believed to be a retaliation for an
earlier Hezbollah attack against an Israeli post inside its
occupied border zone in south Lebanon. One Israeli soldier was
wounded in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of this year, a total of 23 Israeli soldiers
have been killed inside the enclave, which Israel declared in 1985
as a security zone to protect its north from cross-border attacks
by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
In another development in the day, Israeli warplanes blasted
villages and moutainous areas in the western and central sector
of the security zone. The Israel side believed the areas are
hideouts for Hezbollah guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
There have been no reports of casualties, but the air raids
have caused damages on several Lebanese civilians houses and
cars.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, reportedly backed by Iran and
Syria, has been waging a guerrilla war to dislodge
1,000 Israeli occupying troops and its proxy South Lebanon
Army from the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
