<HEADLINE> Angolan President Calls for Isolating Savimbi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos said here Saturday that the only way to achieve
lasting peace in the country is to isolate Jonas Savimbi and his
UNITA military group.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening of the 4th National Congress of the
ruling People's Liberation Movement of Angola (MPLA), Dos Santos
who is also MPLA Chairman said that Savimbi, leader of the
opposition National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) should be isolated politically and militarily because he
is a man bending to kill, sabotage and split.
</P>
<P>
He noted that even the patriotic UNITA members agree to the
decision to isolate Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi and his followers have become agents of foreign
interests and "have been used in ruling the Angolan people and
continuing to exploit the wealth there," said Dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan president called upon the MPLA to mobilize all the
Angolans to fight the enemies against the peace and those agents
of foreign interests.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the congress, MPLA General Secretary
Lopo do Nascimento complained that the United Nations has not
done enough in Angola peace process.
</P>
<P>
Do Nascimento pointed out that as the UNITA repeatedly
contravened the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol, the U.N., ignoring
the will of the Angolan people, put pressure on the Angolan
government to resume dialog with the former rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the stance of the Angolan government is firm:
abandoning "war criminal" Savimbi and seeking for peace with the
sole lawful dialogist UNITA Renovation Commission.
</P>
<P>
The MPLA national congress is scheduled to end on December 10.
At the meeting, 1,275 delegates form 18 provinces across the
country will discuss about the current situation and economic
reform program in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The MPLA has been ruling the country since Angola won its
independence in 1975. Now, the party has nearly one million
members under its banner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
