<HEADLINE> Birth Rate Declines in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The fertility rate in Zambia
declined from 6.5 children per woman in late 1980s to 6.1 in
1996, according to a report released Saturday by the Central
Statistical Office of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The report says that despite the decline, the fertility rate
of Zambian women remains one of the highest in sub-Saharan Africa
as surveys in its neighboring countries show very low fertility
rates in comparison with Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The fertility rate is 4.9 in Botswana, 5.4 in Namibia, 5.8 in
Tanzania and 4.3 in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The fertility of urban Zambian women is much lower than their
counterpart in the rural areas with a urban woman giving birth to
5.1 children and a rural woman 6.9 ones on average, says the
report.
</P>
<P>
It shows that the women who have received secondary education
have the lowest level of fertility at 4.5 compared with a rate of
6.8 children per woman with no education.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, over one third of the Zambian women
become mothers by the time they reach 18 years old and about
two-thirds having a child when they are 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
