<HEADLINE> Syria, Iraq Call for Reviving Tripartite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Syria and Iraq on Saturday
called for reviving the tripartite Syrian-Iraqi-Turkish committee
on water.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Minister of Irrigation Abdul-Rahman Madani and his Iraqi
counterpart Mahmoud Thiab Al-Ahmed made the call in a statement
released following their four-day talks.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers urged the Turkish concerned minister to hold
with them a three-way meeting with a view to reviving the
tripartite committee set up in 1980.
</P>
<P>
During the Syrian-Iraqi talks, the two ministers underlined the
necessity of coordination between Syria and Iraq in all
international arenas concerned with water.
</P>
<P>
They also highlighted the importance of probing a tripartite
agreement with Turkey on sharing the waters of the Euphrates
Tigris rivers in accordance with the international law and
neighborliness as well as the historical ties between the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Water should constitute bridges of peace, communication and
interaction among the three countries, the ministers said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey confines the water quotas to Syrian and Iraq at just 500
cubic meters a second while the two latter countries seek to raise
the figure to 700 cubic meters. Talks on the question have been
frozen since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
