<HEADLINE> Cancellation of Mozambican Debt Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A international conference on
Mozambican external debt ended here Saturday, calling for total
and unconditional cancellation of Mozambique's debt which stands
at some 5.6 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Mozambican government, the World
Bank, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and some
European countries participated in the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by the conference called upon the
Mozambican parliament to coordinate among the parliaments of the
SADC member states so as to take joint actions to seek for debt
exemption for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique also urged coordination between the Mozambican
parliament and those of the debtees so that they can influence
their respective governments and the Bretton Woods Institutions
for the cancellation of the debts.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Mozambique was listed as one of the
candidates for the Heavily-indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) debt
relief initiative.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, 80 percent of Mozambique's foreign debt would be
canceled by mid-1999. But the Mozambican government demands that
all its external debt should be exempted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
