<HEADLINE> 12 Primate Species under Threats of Extinction in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 5 (Xinhua) -- About 12 species of primates in
Nigeria are under threats of extinction as a result of habitat
loss.
</P>
<P>
The species include the white-throated guenon species and
drill monkeys, the News Agency of Nigeria Saturday quoted
environmental scientist Adeboke Adegoroye as saying at the
just-concluded Obafemi Awalowo Foundation Dialog.
</P>
<P>
Adegoroye, Acting Director-General of the Federal
Environmental Protection Agency, alerted the Nigerians that the
country's wildlife is rapidly declining due to habitat loss and
increased pressure from hunters, poachers and bush burning.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some animals such as ceihan, pygmy
hippopotamus, giraffe and the black rhinoceros have already
disappeared from the Nigerian environment.
</P>
<P>
The environment in this most populous African country is being
affected negatively by what he called uncontrolled logging, tree
felling and gas flaring.
</P>
<P>
The gas flaring is a major threat to the Nigerian environment
as it results in acid rain which destroys fresh water fishes and
forests, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the flaring of petroleum-associated gas
in Nigeria alone accounts for 28 percent of total gas flared in
the world.
</P>
<P>
On challenges to Nigeria's environmental management,
Adegoroye said that there are inadequate legal and administrative
instruments for the enforcement of laws on the protection of the
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
