<HEADLINE> PNA Launches Campaign to Collect Illegal Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Sunday launched a campaign to collect illegal
weapons in the self-rule areas required by the latest agreement
signed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli Wye accord reached on October 23
provides that the collection of illegal weapons in Palestinian-run
areas should start seven weeks after the signing of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the campaign called on those
Palestinian citizens who own arms to hand over the illegal weapons
within weeks or apply for a license.
</P>
<P>
A decree issued by the PNA two weeks ago said that anyone, who
has illegal weapons but fails to turn them over, will be sentenced
to six months in jail and fined for 800 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Wye accord also envisages that Israel pulls out its troops
from 13 percent more of the West Bank within three months in
return for intensified Palestinian crackdown on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
But Israel suspended the implementation of the accord last
Thursday, saying it will not resume the troops withdrawal until
the PNA made concessions over such issues as the release of
Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails and the Palestinian
statehood. The Palestinians have threatened to announced an
independent state next May whatever a peace treaty with Israel is
reached or not.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross will come to Israeli and
the Palestinian self-rule areas Thursday to try to restart the
implementation of the Wye agreement to prepare for a upcoming
three-day visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton, which begins
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
