<HEADLINE> Chinese Learning The Importance Of Farm Product Trademarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Until quite recently, Chinese
farmers seldom bothered to apply for a trademark when they
developed a product.
</P>
<P>
So, when some villagers in Quxian County in Zhejiang province
registered their "Yi Pin Hong" brand oranges a few years ago,
their neighbors laughed themselves silly at the foolishness.
</P>
<P>
But, the neighbors' attitude changed in 1995, when oranges
without a brand name couldn't find buyers, resulting in 100
million yuan in losses to local growers. At the same time, Yi Pin
Hong oranges were bought by dealers for 4 times the price of other
oranges.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't need any brand in the past because farm products
were managed by the government," explains one farmer, but now they
see differently. In Zhejiang alone, there have been 4,974
applications for trademarks for everything from tea to mushrooms,
plums, walnuts, and geese.
</P>
<P>
To cultivate better brands, Chinese farmers have tried hard to
improve their techniques and strains and a number of farm
production centers have been established or expanded to produce
high-quality products that are likely to become well-known name
brands.
</P>
<P>
A name-brand farm-product fair here last month attracted over
200,000 people, including some 70 business people from Germany,
Japan, Canada, and elsewhere. More than 130 contracts were signed,
worth 4.7 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
