<HEADLINE> Brown: I Could Do Nothing at Celtic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Celtic general manager
Jock Brown has claimed he was so reviled at Parkhead that
whatever he did his actions would have been twisted and used
against him.
</P>
<P>
Brown left his post by mutual consent earlier this season
after a series of controversies, most notably being blamed by
head coach Wim Jansen for the Dutchman's decision to leave the
club 48 hours after lifting the title.
</P>
<P>
The protracted delay before the appointment of Jozef Venglos
as Jansen's successor also sparked criticism of Brown, who in his
final months at Parkhead refused all contact with the media.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The size of Celtic is ferocious. I didn't appreciate
before I went there ... who could unless they were in the middle
of it all. In these circumstances it was going to be a very
difficult task.
</P>
<P>
"I was told by a player a year ago that he envied me least of
all in the sense that if there was success the coach would take
it - if there was failure I would be blamed.
</P>
<P>
"I have lost track of the (press) accusations because they
were so persistent. It got to the stage where if I had rescued a
toddler from a burning building I would have been accused of
being a child molester.
</P>
<P>
"What I do know is there was a state of affairs created
whereby the perception was that I had power vested in me by the
board which was totally out of the bounds of reality.
</P>
<P>
"I was in the buffer zone. I was between the playing side, the
coaching side and the board side and had to take the flak - I saw
it as part of the job," he added. 
</P>
