<HEADLINE> S. Korean Golfer Regains Omega Order of Merit Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Kang Woon-soon
carved his name into Omega Asian Tour history after a commanding
victory in the 500,000 U.S. dollars Omega PGA Championship at
Clearwater Bay Golf and Country Club here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Completing a remarkable end to the season in Hong Kong, Kang
won by three shots from Chinese Taipei's Hsieh Chin-sheng, to
also claim the Omega Order of Merit title and become the first
player to win back-to-back Omega Tour events.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old South Korean, winner of last week's Perrier
Hong Kong Open, fired a final round four-under-par 66 for a
four-round aggregate of 17-under-par 263, while Hsieh returned a
65.
</P>
<P>
"I really felt the pressure today," admitted Kang after the
victory. "When I was on the practice putting green this morning,
I found it very difficult to settle down on the course. I am so
happy to have won again," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kang, who won the Omega Order of Merit title in 1996, became
only the second player to win four times on Tour along with
Thailand's Boonchu Ruangkit.
</P>
<P>
Kang started the fourth day strokes ahead of Hsieh and he
never let his lead slip to less than three. After a
two-under-par 33 from nine he led by three from China's Zhang
Lian-wei and by four from Hsieh, and with three holes to play the
South Korean led both players by three.
</P>
<P>
Any hopes that Hsieh and Zhang had of catching Kang were
dashed when the steady South Korean birdied 17 before he added
the icing to the cake by holing a 12 footer for birdie on the par
five 18th. A double-bogey on 18 cost Zhang a share of the third
place with American Eric Rustand, who closed with a spectacular
course record leveling eight-under-par 62 for a 12-under-par
tournament total.
</P>
<P>
Ruangkit took the fourth place on 11-under-par after carding a
67 while American Erik Meeks fired a 65 to finish tied fifth with
Zhang a stroke further back.
</P>
<P>
The top prize of 80,750 U.S. dollars brought Kang, who had
been in the seventh spot on the Merit list, over England's Ed
Fryatt up to top the Omega Order of Merit, with a final earning
for the year to 150,771 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Omega Tour's season will be brought to a conclusion next
week with Volvo Asian Matchplay and Hugo Boss Foursomes slated
for December 10-13 at Mission Hills Golf Club in Shenzhen, China.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Lian-wei will compete as a hosting player while other
participants will be the winners of this year's Omega PGA Asian
Tour events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
