<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Region Developing Rapidly with Central Leaders' Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region in southern China has made social and economic progress in
the past 40 years, thanks to special help from central government
leaders, local officials say.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi's political stability, economic development, ethnic
unity and social prosperity are the outcome of the kind attention
shown by three generations of leaders, says Cao Bochun, secretary
of the regional Communist Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
Late Chinese Chairman Mao Zedong visited Guangxi in January
1958, and the autonomous region was officially established in the
year.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, Mao told the autonomous regional Party chief Wei
Guoqing to place greater importance on the unity of the Han,
China's major ethnic group, and the Zhuang, the largest ethnic
group in Guangxi, and 10 other ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
In 1952, the government published its official Zhuang
dictionary, the first of its kind for China's largest ethnic
minorities areas, thus putting an end to the history in which the
Zhuang ethnic group did not has its own written language.
</P>
<P>
In 1965, Premier Zhou Enlai replaced the character then used
for 'Zhuang' with another character with the same pronunciation
that means "strong" or "powerful".
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, late veteran Leader Deng Xiaoping visited the
autonomous region in 1973 and 1986, and gave special instructions
on environmental protection to help develop local tourism.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the central government leaders have paid still
greater attention to Guangxi because it was lagging behind and
ranked the last but one among all provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions in the country in terms of the average annual
per-capita gross domestic product (GDP) in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu Rongji, Li Ruihuan and other
third-generation Chinese leaders have visited the autonomous
region on many occasions and given instructions about how to cope
with different issues and a series of favorable policies and funds
have been provided by the central government to help Guangxi in
social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
And the policies and financial assistances by the central
leadership have paid off. During the Eighth Five-Year Plan
(1991-1996), Guangxi's economy grew six percentage points faster
than the national average, at 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Guangxi's GDP was 206.7 billion yuan, 18.9 times the
figure for 1957, and its per-capita GDP ranked 11th in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
