<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Bangkok Governor Vows to Make Air Clean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok, a metropolis with
severe air pollution, has the chance of entering the new
millennium with clean air thanks to the ambitious environment
projects launched by the city administration.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok governor Bhichit Rattakul is guiding the capital, with
its 6 million-plus population, into a city free of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
In his two-and-a-half years in office, the governor had made
serious efforts to fight the city's air pollution, with several
high profile projects including the campaign for dust-free roads,
stop-checks for vehicles with excessive exhaust fumes, and a ban
on motorists running their engines while parking at public
buildings and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
Bhichit has vowed that the city administration will go all out
to ensure that Bangkok's air become clean in the year to come.
</P>
<P>
"Improving the city's air quality will be the main activity for
the whole new year," the governor told reporters. The city
administration's most obvious achievement, he said, will be the
improvement of the city environment and quality of life.
</P>
<P>
Well-known for his enthusiasm in tackling the air pollution,
Bhichit, a former Bangkok MP, has set up an action group for this
purpose.
</P>
<P>
He successfully gained approval from Bangkok voters by
consistently campaigning against air pollution. The campaign
helped him win more than 700,000 votes in the city governor
election in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok's air pollution comes mainly from about 3 million
registered vehicles, and the number of vehicles is on the rise
despite the economic crisis sweeping the country.
</P>
<P>
With no restrictions on the number of vehicles, it will be hard
for Bhichit to handle this problem. But Bhichit has cards up in
his sleeves.
</P>
<P>
He said a citywide campaign against air pollution will begin in
March, 1999 with the number of vehicle exhaust checkpoints
reaching 200. "By the end of next year, air quality must be
better," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the city administration will launch campaigns to
educate Bangkok residents about how to maintain their car engines
and reduce fumes. For this purpose, the city administration will
receive technical assistance from the World Bank and the United
States Environment Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
The governor has more in his mind. He plans a series of
projects including resurfacing roads and footpaths, building more
bus stops, bicycle lanes, motorcycle parking lots, public drinking
stands, miniature parks, public toilets, tourist information and
municipal police kiosks, pedestrian bridges, planting of trees,
installing more rubbish bins and dredging storm drains.
</P>
<P>
Public transport projects including tram routes along city
canals and public vans are expected to be operational next year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more public recreation areas and sports facilities
will be opened, and those left jobless by the recession will be
employed on the environment projects. Public health services will
be available to more people by the city's medical units, according
to Bhichit.
</P>
<P>
All the projects have won the applaud of Bangkokians. The
governor, however, has many obstacles to remove. Among them is the
lack of money.
</P>
<P>
Some of the projects are controversial and are questioned for
their high cost, including the purchase of palm trees to decorate
the road that runs parallel to the Ramindra-Arjnarong expressway,
and public toilets on Rajdamri road.
</P>
<P>
As measures are being taken to ease the city's air pollution,
the ban on motorists leaving their engines running seems not to be
effective. Most motorists ignored the city's threatened fines,
Security guards at parking lots are often reluctant to warn
motorists to turn their engines off.
</P>
<P>
In the latest controversial case, the city paid the State
Railway of Thailand 555 million baht (15.4 million U.S. dollars)
to convert its golf course, close to Chatuchak Park, into a new
public park.
</P>
<P>
But Bhichit is determined to achieve his goal. "I intend to
give Bangkokians an even better environment and higher quality of
life in the new millennium," he said.
</P>
