<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Minorities Choosing Spouses In New Ways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Young people in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region don't use the old means of love
songs much anymore to find their lifetime partners.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we can find our loved ones just by singing
several love songs," says Xiao Huang, a young Zhuang ethnic group
woman. She found her boyfriend by attending a TV program for
singles.
</P>
<P>
Her father says, "Times have totally changed now. It used to be
rather difficult for men and women to see each other, but nowadays
men can date women by simply calling them." He says he found his
wife by singing lovesongs at the Zhuang song festival on March 3
of the lunar calendar.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists say that this is only one of the many changes in
customs. The greater opportunities to be in contact with Han
people and foreigners have brought great changes to their social
and political lives.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Miao ethnic group in the region's Damiao
Mountain area used to look for their loved ones by going to the
village where the girl lived to sing lovesongs on moonlit
nights. The girls would go to a river or well to drink the water
with the men if they found him suitable.
</P>
<P>
Young men in the Dayao Mountain area could go upstairs directly
to a room especially for young women to declare their love face to
face.
</P>
<P>
But, "This is rarely seen now. The place that used to be used
for dating by young people has become a scenic spot now and that
old way of finding one's love is performed now for tourists,"
according to Feng Wenzhou, deputy chief of Civil Affairs Bureau of
the Jinxiu Yao Autonomous County of Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
It also used to be quite common for cousins or nephews and
nieces to get married in remote villages of the Dong and Yao, but
this is now illegal because of the deformed children that can
result.
</P>
<P>
Marriages within ethnic and between ethnic groups and the Han
are on the increase and these changes reflect their ability to
adapt to the developing world and show the rapid development of
civilization in China, according to Wu Shihua, a scholar of ethnic
minority studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
