<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Official Steps Up Campaign for WTO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi is intensifying his campaign to win the post
of the World Trade Organization (WTO) director-general.
</P>
<P>
Thai News Agency reported on Sunday that Supachai, also
commerce minister, has won strong support from many countries in
Latin America and some African countries during recent talks with
their government officials.
</P>
<P>
Australia had earlier voiced strong support to Supachai, who
now focused his campaign on several African Muslim countries
currently supporting the Moroccan candidate, former Trade Minister
Hassan Abouyoub.
</P>
<P>
Former New Zealand Prime Minister Mike Moore and former
Canadian Trade Minister Roy Maclaren are also contenders.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial tallies suggested that Supachai and Moore were
leading the race.
</P>
<P>
Major WTO members which would have a decisive role in the
selection, including the United States and E.U. countries, have
yet to make public their positions.
</P>
<P>
Under WTO practice, inherited from the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, major decisions should be taken by consensus
among members, now totaling 132 countries.
</P>
<P>
But a November 30 deadline for identifying a leading candidate
around whom a consensus might be built slipped by and the
ambassadors of Switzerland and Brazil, conducting the selection
process, said they needed more time and planned to complete the
task by year end.
</P>
<P>
Also, the idea of a vote has been floated by ambassadors of
Egypt and Pakistan at an informal meeting of the WTO General
Council called to review the situation, although both said
consensus remained the best way.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials said Supachai had gained support after
presenting his policies toward the WTO last month.
</P>
<P>
"Even Cuba and Brazil, which once nominated their own
candidates, lent support for Thailand," an official said.
</P>
<P>
The new director-general will succeed Italian Renato Ruggiero,
who completes his four-year term in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
