<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Y2K Efforts Gain International Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Sunday that international organizations have committed to back
efforts of the Philippine Presidential Commission on year 2000
Compliance to prepare the country for the Y2K, or the "millennium
bug" problem.
</P>
<P>
In a report to President Joseph Estrada, the commission said
these agencies are now focusing their support on the holding of an
International Y2K Summit to be held in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) and the U.S. Federal Reserve Board have already
 promised their support for the summit, it said.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the Philippine summit will have
"tremendous significance" in promoting awareness, getting best
practices and experiences, and updating on the progress of
international efforts to lick the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
But the commission has not proposed the date and the venue of
the summit.
</P>
<P>
The "millennium bug" is a built-in flaw in many computer
systems that could jeopardize a large number of activities in
both the private and public sectors beginning in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Anti Y2K efforts are focused on making sure computer systems do
not mistake the year 2000 for the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
At least seven sectors -- transportation, power, water, health,
 manufacturing, banking and finance and telecommunications and
government services --- may become paralyzed if concerned agencies
 and firms do not prepare them for the Y2K problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
