<HEADLINE> Manila Eyes Agrarian Reform Communities for Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Sunday that it has placed on the fast track the establishment of
agrarian reform communities (ARCs) in the countryside to deliver
basic services to the poor and free them from the clutches of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
These communities will provide beneficiaries not only with full
government assistance to increase their agricultural yields, but
with education, health, child care, shelter and other basic social
services as well, said Secretary Horacio Morales of the Department
of Agrarian Reform in a statement issued here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that around half of the rural poor households would be
able to cross over the income poverty line with the full
implementation of ARCs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"Within these ARCs, farmer beneficiaries receive not just
financing, production, processing, and marketing assistance, they
also get basic social services -- education, health and shelter,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
So far 1,000 ARCs have been set up nationwide with the help of
donor governments and agencies, Morales said.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, this figure hardly covers 10 percent of the
targeted rural poor. 
</P>
