<HEADLINE> Polio Immunization Program Launched in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The first phase of polio
immunization program was launched here Sunday and an estimated 125
million Indian children will be immunized from December 6, 1998 to
January 17, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO), Rotary International and
the Indian government have intensified their polio eradication
efforts this year. Millions of health workers as well as business
and youth volunteers have been mobilized to target areas where
confirmed polio cases have been found and routine immunizations do
not cover in the country.
</P>
<P>
In New Delhi, capital of India, the government has set up more
than 4,000 immunization booths for an estimated 1.9 million
children. About 30,000 volunteers, including students from 160
schools will participate in the event. Intensive door-to-door
campaigns will be conducted in 50 identified high risk areas in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Polio is caused by the wild polio virus which travels at a
lightening speed of infecting almost 200 children before the
disease is detected in the form of paralysis. Every unimmunized
child stands a threat of contracting polio. In India, over 10
percent of the children are still left unimmunized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
