<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition to Launch Attacks against Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 6 (Xinhua) -- With a consensus having
developed among the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance to push against
the militia, Afghan opposition groups are expected to launch
attacks against the Taliban in the northern and eastern parts of
the country during the next ten days.
</P>
<P>
Afghan sources in Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's North West
Frontier Province, told Xinhua that the Afghan opposition leaders
are contemplating to go ahead with their offensives against the
Taliban before the starting of severe cold weather in the
war-battered Afghanistan, especially in the northern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Northern Afghanistan usually receives heavy snowfall during the
months of December, January and February.
</P>
<P>
A three-day summit of the fractured anti-Taliban Northern
Alliance concluded in Panjsher on Saturday with a pledge to
overcome their differences and go for unified attacks against the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
However, Taliban leaders are least concerned about the moot in
Panjsher, saying that the Northern Alliance has died a natural
death.
</P>
<P>
"It does not exist any more," a Taliban leader told Xinhua,
requesting not to be named.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt that the opposition is to launch attacks against
the Taliban forces in Baghlan, Kunduz and Takhar in the north of
Afghanistan and eastern provinces including Nangarhar, Kunar and
Laghman.
</P>
<P>
The Sources said that the Panjsher summit, however, remained
inconclusive to formulate its strategy about the southeastern
provinces where Commander Ahmad Shah Masood has developed
differences with Jamiat-e-islami leader Said Noorullah Emmad.
Emmad is a very influential Rabbani's Jamiat leader in the
southwestern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Sources further said Commander Masud also agreed to provide
military and financial assistance to the commanders in the eastern
provinces. However, he was not happy with performance of the
anti-Taliban commanders in the eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
The sources said, those attended the moot included former
governor of Nangarhar province Abdul Qadeer, former governor of
Laghman province Abdullah Jan Wahidi, head of his newly-formed
faction of Hizb-e-Islami Humayun Jareer and representative of the
Mutawaqil faction of Hizb-e-Wahdat (Shiites group).
