<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Festivals Becoming More Colorful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- "We have a lot of festivals to
celebrate, one after another, because our family has people of
four ethnic groups: the Han, Miao, Dong, and Yao," says Feng
Xiaogang, of Longsheng County in south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has the Yao, Sui, Maonan, Yi, Gin, Gelao, and Dong
ethnic groups, accounting for 39 percent of the province's 46
million people. Longsheng has 5 main ethnic groups: namely the
Miao, Yao, Dong, Zhuang and Han.
</P>
<P>
Different ethnic minorities used to live apart, and festivals
were the only time they got together singing and dancing and
eating, because they were quite poor, says Huang Zhongjing, the
assistant county magistrate.
</P>
<P>
But now, people celebrate their festivals in a totally
different way. They exchange technological and production
information at the festival and hold various celebrations to
attract tourists and businessmen from elsewhere, Huang explains.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
