<HEADLINE> Asian Games Opens in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The 13th Asian Games opened in
the Thai capital of Bangkok on Sunday with an extravaganza
ceremony as the country is still battling the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's King Bhumibol Adulyadej declared the Games open at
the 60,000-seat Rajmangala Stadium of the Hua Mark Sports Complex
here.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing, who is on a four-day official
visit to Thailand, attended the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the ceremony are leaders of the international
sports organizations including the International Olympic Committee
President Juan Antonio Samaranch and the Olympic Council of Asia
President Sheikh Ahmad al-Fahad al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 athletes and officials from 42 countries and
regions are participating in the Games, which features 377 gold
medals in 36 sports.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's only Olympic gold medalist Somrak Khamsing, as the
last runner of the torch relay, became the cynosure of the whole
stadium by setting the cauldron alight, sending the whole audience
into elated acclamation.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is hosting the last Asian Games of the century amid
its most severe financial crisis in decades and a spate of
withdrawals even weeks ahead of the games' opening.
</P>
<P>
Organizers had to make three re-draws in some events as 17
teams had pulled out.
</P>
<P>
But even Sunday night's performance, a feast-for-eye mixture of
song and dance by local pop singers and performers in colorful
costumes, partly reflected the country's determination to fight
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the first act "The Dawn", dusk was transformed to dawn when
the Sun God made its spectacular entrance at the stadium,
symbolizing the wit to overcome the financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
China, which won 126 golds at the last games four years ago, is set
to retain its number one position during the two-week event, with
Japan and South Korea contending for the second place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
