<HEADLINE> Chinese Skaters Win Overall Champions at World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- China's Li Jiajun and Yang
Yang (A) stood atop the men's and women's overall rankings after
the sixth-leg short track speed skating World Cup series
concluded here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Li, who won three golds in the men's 500m, 1,000m and 1,500m
at the Beijing leg, accumulated 98 points after his four-leg
competitions, including Canada, United States, Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
Li defeated South Korean Kim Dong-Sung, who had two points
advantage over the Chinese before the leg and had to settle on
the third with a total of 93 points.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Fabio Carta, who didn't join the Beijing competition,
finished second at 97 points.
</P>
<P>
In the women's competition, China's Yang Yang (A) won the
overall champion with 100 points after pocketing four golds here.
</P>
<P>
Evgenia Radanova of Bulgaria finished runner-up by scoring 98
points, five points ahead of third placer Yang Yang (S) of China.
</P>
<P>
The final standings of each skater was calculated by the four
best results out of the six legs.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yang (A) also led her Chinese teammates Yang Yang (S),
Wang Chunlu and Sun Dan to win the team race with 100 points,
followed by South Korea, 98 points. The United States was third
in 94.
</P>
<P>
On the men's team table, Italy collected 100 points for first
place. China totaled 96, ahead of South Korea with 94.
</P>
<P>
The men's overall title was contested between Li Jiajun and
Kim Dong-Sung. In the day's 1,000m final, Li beat Kim to third
palce, revenging his defeat to Kim at the Nagano Winter Olympics,
where Kim won the gold medal and Li was second.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very nervous when overtaken by others, because the
result matters whether I can take the overall champion," Li told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Li believed that Kim and Terao Satoru of Japan, the fifth in
the event at the Nagano Olympics, didn't perform very well in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Our skaters perfomed very well indeed, " said Xin Qingshan,
coach of the Chinese team. "They always skated better at home
than abroad. That is our problem to be solved."  
</P>
