<HEADLINE> Khatami's Allies Launch New Political Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Allies of Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami have launched a new political party, Islamic
Iran Participation Front (IIPF), to help the president create a
civil society in the country.
</P>
<P>
The IIPF was founded by over 100 political and executive
figures of the country, who are mainly government officials and
deputies of Majlis (Islamic Consultative Assembly).
</P>
<P>
Iran's first female Vice President Masoumeh Ebtekar, Energy
Minister Habibollah Bitaraf, Minister of Post, Telephone and
Telegraph Mohammad Reza Aref, Deputy Foreign Minister for
Asia-Pacific Affairs Mohsen Aminzadeh and Deputy Interior Minister
Mostafa Tajzadeh are reportedly among the founders.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Saturday, the IIPF said the
May 23, 1997 presidential election in Iran has accelerated the
public approach toward a just and alert society.
</P>
<P>
On the threshold of the third decade of the victory of the
Islamic revolution, it said, forging a political-social atmosphere
for organizing institutions and groups is the prime responsibility
felt in the society.
</P>
<P>
The IIPF said promotion of the atmosphere for
dialogue and adherence to the rule of law is the main path
toward optimum utilization of intellectual potentials of the
elite groups as well as dynamism of theoretical and practical
approaches in the society.
</P>
<P>
However, the party did not announce its guiding principles and
its leader. But it is believed that the IIPF will become one of
the most powerful political parties in the country. 
</P>
