<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Takes Men's Crown at NHK Figure Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia's teenage Evgeny
Plushenko captured the men's singles title on Sunday at the NHK
Trophy figure skating tournament in Sapporo, Japan.
</P>
<P>
It's Plushenko's second career Grand Prix victory. He was
followed by Japan's Takeshi Honda and China's Li Chengjiang.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Plushenko, the gold medalist in the Skate
Canada four weeks ago, landed a clean quadruple-triple jump
combination in the free program. So did Li.
</P>
<P>
Plushenko, the bronze medalist in the world championships,
first did the quad-triple jump in the Sun Life Skate Canada
International on Nov. 8 as he finished ahead of Stojko, who won
the silver.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Plushenko started with a quad toe loop and a triple
toe loop combination, followed by a triple axel and a triple toe
loop sequence and five more triple jumps, all in perfect
execution and style.
</P>
<P>
Judges gave him eight 5.9s and a 5.8 of a possible 6.0 for
content and techniques, and a 6.0, six 5.9s and two 5.8s for
presentation.
</P>
<P>
"It was the first 6.0 I've ever received, and I know how
precious a 6.0 mark is,'' Plushenko was quoted as saying. "A
perfect 6.0 mark is an ultimate goal for all the competitors.
Yet, you know, only a few have had the honor."
</P>
<P>
In the compulsory program Friday, Li Chengjiang was second to
Plushenko, and Honda was in third place.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Tatyana Malinina of Uzbekistan won the women's
singles.
</P>
<P>
World champions Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze of
Russia won the pairs title, while Marina Anissina and Gwendal
Peizerat of France won the ice dancing.
</P>
<P>
The NHK Trophy is the sixth and last event in the
International Skating Union's Grand Prix series. Under a
points-scoring system, the series lead to the Grand Prix Final in
Russia in March, two weeks before the world championships in
Finland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
