<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Launches Social Welfare Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Labor and Social Welfare officials said Sunday that under the
program, the Social Security Fund will provide 150 baht (4.2 U.S.
dollars) per head/month for up to two children aged not over six
years old at a time in a family. But only families which have made
contributions to the fund for the past 12 months are qualified for
the benefit.
</P>
<P>
The program is intended to protect those who are not employed
continuously for 12 months and have more than two children.
</P>
<P>
The old-age pension scheme is aimed at those over 55 years
old. The monthly pension is 15 percent of the average monthly
salary over the last five years or 60 months of employment.
</P>
<P>
For instance, retirees with at least 30 years' membership of
the fund on an average monthly salary of 20,000 baht (555 dollars)
for the last five years of employment are qualified for a pension
of 7,000 baht (194 dollars) per month for the rest of their life.
</P>
<P>
If the fund members have made more than 180 monthly
contributions their monthly pension will go up 1 percent for every
year of additional payments.
</P>
<P>
If the members die in 60 months or five years of receiving the
pension, their relatives are entitled to get a sum amounting to 10
times their last monthly pension.
</P>
<P>
Members of the fund will next year make a monthly contribution
of 2 percent of their salary -- 1 percent to cover injuries,
sickness, disability and death under the first phase of the social
safety net and 1 percent to cover child welfare and old-age
pension under the second phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
