<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Committed to Congo (K) Peace: OAU Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim has said that the
regional grouping will work tirelessly to ensure there is a
ceasefire in the war-torn Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking when he met Zambian Presidential Affairs Minister
Eric Silwamba Saturday during a brief stop-over at Lusaka
International Airport en route to South Africa, Salim said the
OAU is actively consulting on ways of finding a solution to the
four-month DRC crisis which is of great concern to Africa, Zambia
Daily Mail reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The government-owned paper quoted Salim as saying his meeting
with Silwamba is part of the process of consultation and that he
would take advantage of his visit to South Africa to continue
with the consultations.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to South Africa on a private visit but I will use
the visit to continue the consultations. We want to ensure there
is a ceasefire in DR Congo," said the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Salim added that the OAU has always understood there are both
internal and external forces to the DRC conflict which has sucked
in at least six foreign countries and it would take that into
consideration in trying to find a solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the OAU is going to involve the Uganda and
Rwanda-backed rebels fighting against DRC President Laurent
Kabila in future talks, Salim diplomatically evaded the question.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever will be agreed upon, we will involve all parties.
But the modalities will depend on situation to situation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believed Salim's visit to South
Africa is aimed at not only conducting consultations with
President Nelson Mandela who, from the very beginning of the war,
has been advocating for a peaceful solution, but also persuading
South Africa, a regional power, to play active rule in resolving
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DRC peace talks scheduled for this week in
Zambian capital Lusaka has been postponed to next week, a senior
State House official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
DRC leader Kabila is said to be ready for the Lusaka talks
during which a peace deal will probably be hammered out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
