<HEADLINE> Nepali Bridegroom Tested HIV-Positive Before Wedding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A Nepalese bridegroom was
tested HIV-positive just six hours before the wedding ceremony
slated for Saturday, the official RSS news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He was one of the 1,175 persons in the Himalayan kingdom who
were found HIV-positive in voluntary blood tests and 108 of them
have died, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Till the fateful blood test was carried out, the youth, living
in Lalitpur neighboring Kathmandu, felt himself a perfect groom
waiting for the happy hour, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The finding resulted in an immediate termination of the
wedding.
</P>
<P>
"Thank God, I was saved from the jaws of death. A friend who
saved me from this horrible situation is a real God for me," the
bride was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Last year, another youth infected with HIV, the virus that
causes AIDS, died a few months after marriage.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization projected that Nepal will have
50,000 AIDS cases by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
