<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brother of Ugandan President Admits Buying Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni's brother Salim Saleh has admitted that he bought Uganda
Commercial Bank (UCB) from Westmont Land Asia of Malaysia through
Greenland Investment.
</P>
<P>
Salim Saleh, who is also Museveni's security advisor and a
major general, admitted this after months of intensive media
pressure for the truth to come out on the relationship between
him, Greenland Investment, Westmont and UCB, the New Vision daily
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper broke the news on July 6 and Saleh has
persistently denied buying the bank since then. In November, he
denied before members of Parliament any involvement in the UCB
deal.
</P>
<P>
In a three-page statement he issued Saturday, Saleh also
announced his withdrawal from the deal in what he said was "to
save the government, the Bank of Uganda" and all stakeholders the
embarrassment over the affair.
</P>
<P>
He said he had used Greenland Investment to pay for UCB. This
purchase was made to rescue the only fully Uganda bank of
substance and history from foreign control, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Greenland Investment also threatened recently to sue the New
Vision newspaper over the reports it made on the affair.
</P>
<P>
The government sold its 51 percent shares in UCB to Westmont
at 11 million U.S. Dollars. The sale agreement was signed here on
October 26, 1997 but payment was not made until April of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Saleh's statement said that under a purported agreement dated
February 26, 1998, Westmont transferred all its newly-bought
shares to Greenland Investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
