<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Saturday that it was
disappointed at Libya's disagreement to a definitive arrangement
for handing over two suspects in the 1988 bombing of Pan Am flight
103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The State Department expressed the disappointment after U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan failed to secure a clear-cut
agreement on the handover of the suspects during his talks with
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in a desert tent in Libya. "We are
disappointed that Libya is still not in compliance with the
Security Council resolutions. Compliance means turnover of the two
suspects for trial," State Department spokesman James Foley said.
(US-Libya-Lockerbie)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat pledged Saturday
not to enter into any military alliance against Israel and vowed
to renounce armed struggle against the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"For our part, we wish to emphasize that the Palestinian side
does not seek today, and will not seek tomorrow, to enter into any
military struggle or any arms race with Israel or with any other
party in the area," he said in a speech at Sweden's parliament.
Arafat arrived in Sweden earlier in the day to celebrate the 10th
anniversary of his statement in Stockholm which recognized
Israel's right to exist. The statement laid the groundwork for the
historic Mideast peace accord in Oslo in 1993.
(Sweden-Palestine-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Macedonian Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski will
visit Brussels on Monday and Tuesday to discuss the deployment in
Macedonia of a NATO rapid reaction force, according to latest news
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, which will be the first time for Georgievski
since he took office as prime minister on November 30, Georgievski
will meet with NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, EU
commissioner Hans Vanderbruch and OSCE officials. Last Wednesday,
the Macedonian government formally approved the stationing of NATO
troops on its soil to guarantee the safety of international
monitors in the ethnic Albanian-populated Yugoslav province of
Kosovo. (Macedonia-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said the
European Union (EU) foreign ministers will study on Monday the
feasibility of dealing with the case of Ocalan on a European level.
</P>
<P>
Dini told reporters Saturday in Reggio Emilia, northern Italy,
that the monthly meeting of the EU's 15 ministers in Brussels
would provide an opportunity for "seeing whether a European
solution for trying Ocalan has the necessary backing." Abdullah
Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdistan Workers' Party fighting
for Kurdish autonomy in southeast Turkey, was detained in Rome on
November 12 and is now under house arrest in Rome on the basis of
a German arrest warrant. (Italy-Ocalan-EU) 
</P>
</TEXT>
