<HEADLINE> Mayor Verdict Shocks Ugandans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The conviction in Boston, the
United States, of Uganda's capital city mayor Nasser Sebaggala
has sent shock waves among residents of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Some people in a market here became violent Saturday when
arguments heated up with Sebaggala supporters saying that the
whole thing was engineered by the government while others said
the mayor was indeed at fault, the Monitor paper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Most people, however, were glued to radio sets tuning on to
British Broadcasting Corporation and Voice of America programs to
update themselves with the final verdict of the four-week's case.
</P>
<P>
The jury in a Boston court announced that Sebaggala, Kampala's
first directly-elected mayor, was found guilty of all eight
counts of bank fraud, transportation of forged checks and lying
to U.S. customs officers.
</P>
<P>
The report said the 51-year-old mayor will be sentenced on
February 23, 1999, and faces a 21-27 month jail term.
</P>
<P>
The mayor was arrested on June 13 at the Kennedy International
Airport in New York after attending an international conference
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Not being a member of the ruling National Resistance Movement,
Sebaggala was elected mayor of Kampala city in April in a hotly
contested race in which he defeated four other candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
