<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Retain Basketball Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese cagers are aiming at
retaining the Asiad title to tie the games' record of four
straight golds set by the Philippines in the early 1950s, China's
head coach Wang Fei said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
China had won four gold medals in Asiad men's basketball
tournament and three of them came in the last three Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
With their young and talented 2.12-meter center Wang Zhizhi and
Asian all-stars Hu Weidong and Gong Xiaobin, the Chinese team
would accept nothing except the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
"We come here for the gold," said Wang Fei, "and I think the
real contest wouldn't begin until the semi-final round when the
four strongest teams meet."
</P>
<P>
The four strongest teams Wang referred to are defending
champion China, last year's Asian Championship winner South Korea,
the all-pro Philippines and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fei thinks that China's tough rival is South Korea, who
used world-class long shots to upset five-time champion China in
last year's Asian championships. And this time in Bangkok, their
long range fire will be sharper with the upcoming young shooter
Cho Sang-hyun, who won the MVP at the William Jones Cup this
summer in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has formed their strongest ever team with top
pro stars and hopes to retain their past glory.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines have very good outside players but their
bigmen still lack of skills and strength to play against us, even
they have the sizes of 2.15m or 2.10m as we do" said power forward
Gong Xiaobin, captain of the Chinese team who led his team to a
78-70 win over the Philippines team last July.
</P>
<P>
Japan could not be counted out either as they came away from
the World Championships with one win and the 14th place finishing,
better than South Korea's 16th. They will mainly pin their hope
on Michael Takahashi and his Asian All-Star teammate Makato
Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
The basketball competition will begin on December 8 and end on
December 19. All the teams will take the Asiad tournament as a
warmup tournmaent for next year's Asian Championship, which will
decide the only berth for Asian teams to compete in the 2000
Sydney Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
