<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central and Western China Stresses High-Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 6 (Xinhua) -- China's vast central and
western regions are turning to develop high-tech industries in
order to gain an advantageous position in future regional economic
 competition.
</P>
<P>
For example, central China's Henan Province recently adopted
various policies to promote development of both the new and high
techology sectors, and industrialize related research findings.
The province will allocate 50 million yuan annually for high
technology development beginning in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Henan Province will also encourage high-tech businesses and
scientists.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time the provincial government adopted so
many measures to promote high-tech industries," said Zhao Chen,
deputy director of the province's Committee of Science and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
Underdeveloped Shaanxi Province in northwest China is another
example. It has decided to increase 30 million yuan every year for
the development of its high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
The province is now implementing a program to integrate science
and technology with economic growth, focusing on some high and new
technological development zones in Xi'an and Baoji cities.
</P>
<P>
Against the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, provinces in
China's developed eastern part have managed to maintain economic
growth. However, central and western regions have been struggling
with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
So, their best choice is to develop high-tech in a bid to
restructure local industries and create new demand, a leading
official notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
