<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Minority Groups Preserving Culture And Traditions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Scenes from major modern
Chinese city life can also be found in the capital of China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region: tall buildings, overpasses,
Mcdonald's hamburgers, and a lot of cars.
</P>
<P>
Most visitors probably don't even know that a million members
of 35 different ethnic groups live in the city and some might even
think that their ethnic identity is weakening, judging from their
appearance.
</P>
<P>
However, Tan Shengmin, deputy director of the Guangxi Research
Institute of the Zhuang Ethnic Minority, has a different view,
explaining that the Zhuang and other ethnic minorities have not
been assimilated by the Han as some Western scholars have said,
but have enhanced the consciousness of their own ethnic background
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Tan, who is a member of the Zhuang ethnic group, wears the same
clothes as the Han and writes in standard Chinese, but speaks the
fluent Zhuang language, in a city where 75 percent of the people
don't speak standard Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Tan is collecting historical materials on the Zhuang culture
and says that the Zhuangs still hold on to many of their customs.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has 37 ethnic minority groups, of which the Zhuang is
the largest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Minority Group Preserving Culture And Traditions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now, all over Guangxi, people are collecting ethnic minority
data, building museums of folk culture, and publishing works in
ethnic languages.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic minority groups have a splendid culture that rivals that
of the Han, according to Meng Songyi, curator of the Du'an Yao
Autonomous County museum, who plans to go to Beijing to apply for
a loan for a new museum. This idea has attracted the attention of
the central government, which has a plan to allocate loans for
cultural projects in the region.
</P>
<P>
Some scholars say that one of the main causes of the strong
ethnic identity after the reforms and opening up is the increase
in economic and cultural exchanges with the outside world. The
market economy is another factor, Tan Shengmin says.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Luocheng Mulam Autonomous County plans to
revive traditional festivals to attract Mulams living in other
parts of the country back to invest and help push up local
economic development. Other ethnic minority groups are collecting
folk songs and customs for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
China introduced a system of regional autonomy at the beginning
of the 1950s that allowed ethnic minority groups to manage
regional economic and cultural affairs on their own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
