<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Balconies Becoming More Beautiful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Small gardens have begun to
appear in parts of Wuhan in central China's Hubei Province -- but
they're actually balconies decorated with flowers and song birds.
</P>
<P>
Balconies used to be storage space for odds and ends, something
that didn't make the city look particularly good.
</P>
<P>
Gao Liang, a hospital employee, recently moved to Evergreen
Gardens, a new residential area, and still remembers how he had to
live on 3 sq.m. of balcony for twenty years, just room enough for
a single bed.
</P>
<P>
Even so, he says he was fortunate to have his own space,
because most children at that time had to live in the same space
as their brothers and sisters. Gao's new 125-sq.m. apartment has
two living rooms and two balconies, one of them just off one of
the bedrooms. The other is just off the kitchen. Gao spent nearly
10,000 yuan (1,200 U.S. dollars) on decorating the balconies,
2,000 yuan of that for flowers, miniature trees and a rockery.
</P>
<P>
Per capita floor space for the entire city has gone from 3.3
Sq.m. to 8.8 sq.m. in 20 years and balconies are seldom used as
kitchens or storage rooms any more, because newer apartments have
storage spacew built in.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
