<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Reforms Management of Public Utilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province is gradually introducing the market economic system in
the management of public utilities.
</P>
<P>
Related innovations have helped public utilities overcome
financial problems and achieve sustainable development and
measures are introduced to attract funding for further development.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government initiated the reform of public
utilities management in 1997. Reform measures included permitting
individuals and foreign enterprises to participate in public
transportation, and ventures supplying water, gas and heating, all
of which were formerly controlled by the local government.
</P>
<P>
Related statistics show the province has used over three
billion yuan (360 million U.S.dollars) in foreign funding for
water purification projects.
</P>
<P>
The Shenyang Transportation Group Ltd. has earned over 250
million yuan in land-use fees for tracts of land covering
100,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the First Heating Supply Enterprise has issued
stocks valued at 120 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Government officials note that private taxi companies account
for 75 percent and private liquefied petroleum gas stations take
25 percent of the total number of related operations in the
province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
