<HEADLINE> 40 Injured in Clashes Before Polls in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- At least 40 people were injured,
four of them seriously, in clashes on Saturday between activists
of Bangladesh's ruling and opposition parties in northwestern
Pabna district ahead of a by-election there, press reports said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The clashes occurred between supporters of the ruling
Bangladesh Awami League (BAL) and the major opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) over campaigning for the by-election of
Pabna-2 constituency, scheduled for December 10.
</P>
<P>
The seat of the constituency was vacated following the death of
a BAL member of parliament earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Several houses were set on fire during the clashes and police
arrested five people in connection with the clashes, according to
the reports.
</P>
<P>
Post and Telecommunications Minister Mohammad Nasim, Sate
Minister for Information Abu Sayeed and several other government
officials had campaigned for their candidate in the district.
</P>
<P>
The BNP charged that the campaigning by the ministers and
government officials violated election rules, but the charge was
denied by the BAL.
</P>
<P>
The BNP had formed 14 teams for conducting the election
campaign in 14 unions of the Bera-Sujanagar constituency and its
Chairperson Begum Kaleda Zia would start her two-day election
campaign from Monday, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Four candidates from different parties are contesting for the
seat, but the by-election is mainly a competition between the BAL
and the BNP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
