<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Takahashi Breaks Asian Best in Marathon, Wins 1st Gold of Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Takahashi Naoko shattered the
Asian best time of the women's marathon as she romped home to take
the first gold medal of the 13th Asian Games with a fabulous time
of 2:21:47 here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese led the all the way from the start, overcoming the
humidity and heat to trim over three minutes off the previous mark
of 2:24:07, set by 5,000 meters Chinese Olympic chamion Wang
Junxia on her home soil in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Kai Tomoko of Japan and Kim Chang of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea ran almost shoulder to shoulder into the stadium
for the final 400 meters. Kim beat Kai in the stretch to win the
silver in 2:34:55. Kai had to settle for the bronze in 2:35:01.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't expected such a good time. It's too hot, the most
important thing was to battle against myself," said the
26-year-old Takahashi, whose previous personal best was 2:25:48.
</P>
<P>
China's hope to win the first gold medal of the Asian Games before
this evening's opening ceremony turned into a nighmare as pre-race
favorite Pan Jinhong of China wound up a distant fourth in 2:37:29, a
far cry from her personal best of 2:26:39.
</P>
<P>
Her fellow Chinese Wang Yanfang, who sprained her feet before
coming to Bangkok, lagged far behind at 13 km and finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
"It's a great regret that I failed to win a medal for China,"
said the tearful Pan, Chinese national champion and winner of
Beijing international marathon in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Pan said that she had not adjusted herself to Bangkok's weather
and didn't feel good before the race.
</P>
<P>
"Takahashi was too strong," she said. "I wanted to keep up with her
after 30km, but it was impossible since the gap was too big."
</P>
<P>
Takahashi headed the field of 12 runners away after the start
of the 42.195km race of stamina and endurance which started at
6:30 a.m. in Ayutthaya, 70 kilometers to the north of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
With 15km run Takahashi established a lead of around six minutes
over the chasing pack of six women led by Pan.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese, who placed only fifth in 2:31:32 in the national
rankings, displayed top form and covered the first 25km in
1:22:08, extending her leading margin to three kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The second group could hardly pose threat and Takahashi kicked
in a solo run to win the Games' most grueling race and avenged
Japan's defeat in the event at the Hiroshima Asian Games four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Under such difficult conditions, the first thing is to gain
confidence," she said.
</P>
<P>
She was given a Japanese national flag, smiled and waved to the
supporters after crossing the finish line.
</P>
<P>
"If I have opportunity to run in the world championships next
year and the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000," she said, "I think I
can win there. "
</P>
<P>
Takahashi said there was no secret behind her success and rapid
improvement in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
"It's my coach that turned me into the Asian Games champion. I
just followed his instructions," she said.
</P>
<P>
Her coach Yoshio Koide said this victory was of "special
significance" since the gold was the only one awarded before the
opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Koide, also coach of last year's world marathon champion Suzuki
Hirom, said he was also surprised at Takahashi's time.
</P>
<P>
"I expected she could run a time between 3:22:00 and
3:23:00," he said. "Now, I hope she can win the world championship
next year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
