<HEADLINE> Dhaka, Yangon to Hold Talks on Refugee Repatriation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and Myanmar will hold
official talks on December 16 to expedite the repatriation of
Rohingya refugees, a Bangladesh Foreign Ministry official said
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The talks will also discuss border trade, the land mine problem
in the border areas, maritime boundary and development of
communications between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The talks will precede a state minister-level meeting of the
Bangladesh, India, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, Thailand Economic
Cooperation to be held here from December 17 to 19.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of the Myanmar refugees, now staying in two
camps in southeastern Bangladesh's Cox's Bazar district, moved
very slowly, the official told Xinhua. It would take more than 10
years to complete the repatriation of the 21,000 refugees, he
added.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the latest arrangement between the two
countries, some 50 refugees would be sent back to Myanmar every
Wednesday, but only 71 were repatriated during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Some 230,000 out of 250,000 Myanmar Rohingyas, who crossed the
border into Bangladesh in early 1991 and took shelter in
southeastern Bangladesh, have returned voluntarily so far.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of the refugees stopped in July 1997
reportedly as a result of the refugees' refusal to return and
resumed in late November this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
