<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimmers Face Uphill Battle in Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Against a full-fledged Japanese
legion, the absentee-depleted Chinese swimming contingent faces a
herculean task of keeping its supremacy in the pool at the 13th
Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in eight years, the Chinese swimmers are
being tuned down as underdogs for the quadrennial regional sports
gala where swimmers from 29 teams will start to splash the pool on
Monday to chalk off the second biggest cake with 32 golds at
stake.
</P>
<P>
"We will make our utmost efforts to win golds, but it's rather
hard to edge over Japan in gold tally," said Chinese swimming
spokesman Shi Tianshu.
</P>
<P>
"Japan is a traditional swimming power in Asia and hatches a
batch of top-notched swimmers such as Mai Nakamura, Masami Tanaka
and Ayari Isoda," Shi said. "Japan enjoys one-upmanship in a lot
of events against our a few."
</P>
<P>
To make things even worse, China is to miss world record holder
Le Jingyi, a once formidable 23-year-older who captured the sole
swimming gold for China in Atlanta Olympics. The star swimmer has
decided to skip the Games to funnel her energy into university
campus.
</P>
<P>
He Cihong, another Chinese world record holder, was kept away
from the Games as she flunked in the trials, while Liu Limin,
dubbed as Butterfly Queen of China, retired late last year to
aboard for the United States for collegiate career.
</P>
<P>
The absence of these stars saps China's strength in the pool
without a slim of doubt, dimming its prospect to refrain from
losing to Japan, said Zhang Xiong, head coach of the Chinese
swimming team.
</P>
<P>
"China and Japan have competed head to head in the pool
throughout the 1990s," said Zhang, "But in the Asian Games, China
only beat Japan in 1990."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese swimmers notched up 23 golds in the 1990 Beijing
edition against Japan's seven, toppling their arch rivals for the
first time as swimming pace-setters in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Four years later in Hiroshima, the Chinese swimmers were
plunged into an abyss despite a 25-5 margin against the Japanese
in gold hunt as seven of them failed the doping tests.
</P>
<P>
Another four years went by, the Asian Games returns to the Thai
soils for the third time, where the 43-year-old Zhang foresees his
proteges to be sniped ferociously by the Japanese swimmers as they
are coveting to retain the top spot.
</P>
<P>
Japan has marked advantages in 13 events while China has seven,
leaving the remaining 12 wide open, Zhang explained.
</P>
<P>
"Since Japan has pinned its greatest hopes on its swimmers, the
battle against it in Bangkok will be very tough," the
husky-pitched coach Zhang said, "But so long as we unite to bring
out our best, we still have the chance to level against Japan."
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan, both teenager world record holders in
the women's 400m and 200m individual medleys respectively, are the
trump cards for coach Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Chen struck golds in the 400m individual medley
and 400m freestyle and the 19-year-old Wu triumphed in the 200m
medley in the World Swimming Championships in Perth in January.
</P>
<P>
In the Bangkok Games, Chen is to compete in five events of the
200m and 400m individual medleys, the 200m and 400m freestyles,
400-meter freestyle and the 4x200 freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
For his male disciples, Zhang said Zeng Qiliang and Fu Yong are
sure to take golds in their respective specialities, the 100m
breaststroke and 200m backstroke.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's Japanese peer Tsuytoshi Aoki seemed more like a
diplomat in fielding the question concerning the swimming battle
between China and Japan in the Games.
</P>
<P>
"The swimming in China is downwarding while Japan is upbeating,
but China is still strong enough as it is fielding in its best
swimmers here," Aoki said, "I hope my swimmers will perform to
their best and beat their Chinese opponents to stand atop of the
podium."
</P>
<P>
Japan is stronger than China in the men's events but weaker in
the women's swimming, and will take a maximum of 10 swimming
golds, the 51-year-old Japanese forecasted in a wary tone.
</P>
<P>
But Sri Lanka's swimming coach Rizvi Zain rippled the tune of
Aoki, saying "Japan has more good swimmers and I'm sure Japan will
beat China in the swimming pool in Bangkok." 
</P>
</TEXT>
