<HEADLINE> Railing Collapses at U.S. Army-Navy Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- a railing collapsed in the
stands during the U.S. Army-Navy game Saturday, injuring nine
cadets and prep school students and broke one person's neck in
Philadelphia, the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, the railing in the first
row of the east end zone in Veterans Stadium collapsed when the
fans were cheering after Army took a 31-30 lead with 7"33 left in
the game.
</P>
<P>
The game, which Army won 34-30, was suspended for 31 minutes
as four ambulances drove into the field. Army Captain John
Cornelio said the injuries included sprained ankles, necks and
backs.
</P>
<P>
Cornelio said: "We're extremely worried. We're concerned
because cadets were injured. That's serious stuff."
</P>
<P>
The injured were four cadets from the U.S. Military Academy at
West Point, and five students from academy prep school.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the railings in the stands, used only for
football, were held together by duct tape. It wasn't known
whether the incidents were related. 
</P>
