<HEADLINE> 18 Foreigners Arrested in Cuba for Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Cuban authorities have detained
18 foreigners allegedly linked to an international drug
trafficking ring, the official newspaper Granma reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The alleged drug traffickers were arrested between November 6
to November 16. They planned to take 53.5 kilograms of cocaine
and 1.32 kilograms of hashish from Jamaica to the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Among them, seven were Canadian nationals who came from Montego
Bay, Jamaica. They were detained at the Jose Marti International
Airport of Havana when they were trying to smuggle into the United
Kingdom 37.868 kilograms of cocaine hidden in 65 plastic
clothes-hangers and nine plastic suitcases.
</P>
<P>
This could be considered the biggest international drug
trafficking operation dismantled by the Cuban authorities at an
airport, Granma said.
</P>
<P>
In a previous case, three Jamaican nationals were arrested in
the same airport for 165 capsules of hashish totalling 1.32
kilograms in their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
The Jamaicans, who also came from Montego Bay, told the Cuban
authorities that they were going to deliver the drug to a Canadian
citizen in Havana.
</P>
<P>
Other four Jamaicans were arrested between November 13 and 15
as they arrived in Havana with 15.65 kilograms of cocaine in their
luggage.
</P>
<P>
Investigations proved all those foreigners were linked to the
same drug trafficking ring. Four British citizens who were said to
be in charge of taking the drug out of Cuba were also arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
