<HEADLINE> Thai Opposition Said Unable to Topple Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sunday's Bangkok Post quoted New Aspiration Secretary-General
Sanoh Thienthong as saying the opposition, however, would continue
to block the government from carrying out the sixth letter of
intent to the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
He said his party hoped to show the country that promises made
to the IMF were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
"We only want to use parliament as a forum for all parties
concerned to debate whether the letter of intent to obtain the IMF
loan violated the constitution and whether economic measures
required by the IMF will put the country at a disadvantage," Sanoh
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the sixth letter of intent to the IMF, approved by the
government earlier this month, the IMF will grant Thailand 4.74
billion U.S. dollars as part of the 17.2-billion-dollar bailout
package promised soon after the financial crisis broke out last
year.
</P>
<P>
The opposition maintained that Thailand had lost sovereignty
to the IMF by accepting its conditions for the bailout package.
</P>
<P>
Sanoh said the opposition will submit a petition to the
parliament next week seeking an impeachment of the cabinet for
alleged abuse of authority in issuing the letter of intent without
parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
He said the opposition needed to muster the support of 75
percent of the members of both houses to remove the cabinet.
However, he said it did not have enough members to do this.
</P>
<P>
"We have no intention to bring down the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said people would benefit from the debate because
they would understand more about the issue.
</P>
<P>
Suriyasai Katasila, deputy secretary-general of the Campaign
for Popular Democracy, said the Constitutional Court should be
asked to rule on whether the letter of intent was issued in
violation of the constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
