<HEADLINE> U.S. Disappointed at Libya's Stand on Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Saturday that it was disappointed at Libya's disagreement to a
definitive arrangement for handing over two suspects in the 1988
bombing of Pan Am flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The State Department expressed the disappointment after U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan failed to secure a clear-cut
agreement on the handover of the suspects during his talks with
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in a desert tent in Libya.
</P>
<P>
"We are disappointed that Libya is still not in compliance with
the Security Council resolutions. Compliance means turnover of the
two suspects for trial," State Department spokesman James Foley
said.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Washington had seen reports out of Tripoli but was
waiting to hear directly from Annan. "This has gone on for far too
long," he said, noting that the 10th anniversary of the tragedy
was fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 for its refusal
to hand over the two suspects -- Abdel Basset Ali Mohamed
al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhiman, two alleged intelligence
agents, who were accused by the U.S. and Britain of blowing up the
Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie on December 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
A total of 270 people were killed, 259 on the plane and 11 on
the ground, including 189 American citizens.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the U.S. and Britain agreed to Libya's
demand to set up a court in the Netherlands for the trial of the
two suspects before Scottish judges under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Annan made a lightning trip to Libya in the hope of securing a
definitive agreement for the turnover of the two suspects, but
came away without a firm accord, saying some outstanding issues
remained to be overcome.
</P>
<P>
But he said "considerable progress" has been made.
</P>
<P>
"You can take it that we have moved ahead and made considerable
progress" in resolving the dispute, he told reporters after his
meeting with Gaddafi Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
