<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Textile Industry Facing Tougher Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A tougher situation is expected
for China's textile exports next year, further hampering efforts
to lift the textile sector out of the red, according to a report
in today's Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
China's textile exports dropped 3.7 percent in the first ten
months of this year, compared to the same period of 1997, to 35.87
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Garment exports, which have maintained rapid growth rates over
the past few years, reported negative growth for the first time in
October.
</P>
<P>
The declines mainly resulted from the negative impact of the
lingering Asian financial crisis, Fan Min, a division chief of the
Industry Administration Department of the State Textile Industry
Bureau, was cited as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the January-October period, Chinese textile exports
under quota control to the European Union, the United States,
Canada and Turkey rose 1.9 percent from a year ago to 4.8 billion
U.S. dollars, according to Chinese Customs statistics.
</P>
<P>
Yet exports of textiles made in inland China to the Republic of
Korea, Hong Kong and Macao, and Japan plunged 27.5 percent, 11.1
percent and 5.6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Fan predicted that as the negative consequences of the Asian
financial crisis unfold next year, Chinese textile exporters will
face even more difficult times.
</P>
<P>
To make matters worse, the cost of taking part in this year's
public bidding for the 1999 quotas for 21 categories of
best-selling textile exports will raise the exporting costs,
according to some Chinese textile firms.
</P>
<P>
All this will make things more difficult for the country's
loss-stricken textile sector, as 40 percent of the sector's output
is sold abroad each year, Fan said.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry has experienced deficits for five
consecutive years, and more than 40 percent of the country's
textile companies are now on the brink of bankruptcy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
