<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Housewives Get Education on HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 208,000 Myanmar
housewives have got health education on HIV/AIDS prevention under
a training program jointly run by a non-governmental women's
organization and a U.N. agency.
</P>
<P>
The program, undertaken by the Myanmar Maternal and Child
Welfare Association (MMCWA) and the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF),
was first conducted in 27 townships and has been further expanded
to 69 townships now.
</P>
<P>
The MMCWA has been actively involved in HIV/AIDS prevention and
 control projects as part of Myanmar's national health plan (NHP)
since 1993. The present five-year NHP (1996-2001) is under
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Marking the World AIDS Day here on Saturday, Myanmar Minister
of Health Major-General Ket Sein said that in some areas of the
country, some pregnant Myanmar women have been found infected with
HIV, the majority of them through their husbands.
</P>
<P>
He added that some young Myanmar girls in the border areas have
been lured with work and monetary incentives to the neighboring
countries and eventually ended up being forced into sex trade
resulting in infection with HIV.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government, in collaboration with NGOs, has
introduced programs for protecting young people especially girls
against exploitation and violence, obtaining assistance and
cooperation from four U.N. agencies and 13 NGOs inside and outside
the country for HIV/AIDS prevention activities.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar formed the National AIDS Committee in 1989 at the
central level with the participation of various government
departments and NGOs such as the MMCWA for the fight against
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
According to available official data, there were 17,846 HIV
positive people and 2,337 AIDS cases in Myanmar as of the end of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
