<HEADLINE> Brazil Says No to Pinochet's Stopover If UK Releases Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government will
not permit the plane carrying Chile's former president Augusto
Pinochet to make a technical stop on its territory if Britain
agrees to release the general now detained in London.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made before Britain's House of Lords voted
against the immunity of the former Chilean military chief last
month, the newspaper Folha de Sao Paulo said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The British government is expected to decide on Friday whether
it would extradite Pinochet to Spain on judicial requests or it
would send him back to Chile.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso vowed "all the
solidarity to the Chilean government in its negotiations related
to the Pinochet episode, but not to the point of supporting the
general himself."
</P>
<P>
Cardoso will discuss the Pinochet matter with his Chilean
counterpart Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle in a private meeting on
Wednesday in Rio de Janeiro, where the two presidents will
participate in a Southern Common Market (Mercosur) summit.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur groups Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. Chile
and Bolivia joined it as associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
