<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Pledges Not to Enter Military Alliance Against Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat pledged Saturday not to enter into any military alliance
against Israel and vowed to renounce armed struggle against the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"For our part, we wish to emphasize that the Palestinian side
does not seek today, and will not seek tomorrow, to enter into any
military struggle or any arms race with Israel or with any other
party in the area," he said in a speech at Sweden's parliament.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Sweden earlier in the day to celebrate the
10th anniversary of his statement in Stockholm which recognized
Israel's right to exist. The statement laid the groundwork for the
historic Mideast peace accord in Oslo in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In the address to Swedish legislators, Arafat said he
understood "the depth of the fears of the Israeli people" and
their concerns on the security issue.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here expected an Israeli welcome to this new moderate
tone as Israel would definitely not want to see Palestinians in
military alliance with such close neighbors as Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Arafat reiterated the call to solve the Palestinian refugee
issue, warning that without a fair solution to this problem, it
would be impossible for the Palestinian side to strike a final
peace deal with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The analysts noted that the warning was couched in the harshest
wordings in the entire speech.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, however, did not make any reference to the sovereignty
issue of Jerusalem, which is wanted by both the Palestinians and
the Israelis for their capital, saying only that it should be kept
open to all people and not cut apart by borders, barriers or
blocks.
</P>
<P>
Neither did he repeat previous vows to declare a Palestinian
state unilaterally by May 4 next year.
</P>
<P>
Pressed by journalists at the press conference that followed,
Arafat merely replied that Palestine had declared itself to be an
independent state as far back as in 1988 and has so far been
recognized by 127 countries.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's address was heard by Israeli representatives to the
anniversary celebration -- parliamentary whip for the ruling
right-wing Likud party Meir Shitrit and opposition Labor spokesman
Yossi Beilin, who also made speeches on the importance of
Israeli-Palestinian peace.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by representatives from Egypt,
Norway, Russia, the United States, the European Union and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had originally been scheduled to travel to Oslo Sunday
following his stay in Sweden but canceled the trip "due to the
critical situation" in the Palestinian territories where clashes
were reported between some Palestinians and Israeli police.
</P>
<P>
His aide said he wanted to return early to the territories for
timely actions to ease the tension there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
