<HEADLINE> S. Lanka Asks for Loan to Prevent Sea Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
requested a soft loan of 74 million U.S. dollars from the Asian
Development Bank to take long-term measures to arrest sea erosion
in the country, the official The Sunday Observer said.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries and Aquatic Resources Development Minister Mahinda
Rajapakse told the paper that his ministry also plans to build two
fisheries harbors at Negombo and Chilaw with this loan.
</P>
<P>
However, he said priority will be given to the south, which is
the most affected by sea erosion.
</P>
<P>
Sea erosion in the country, particularly along the southern
coast, has become a major problem for Sri Lanka in recent years.
The erosion has been mainly attributed to illegal coral mining.
</P>
<P>
It is largely responsible for displacing several thousand
families from their homes near the coastal belt in the south of
the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The short-term measures of putting up of either stone buffers
or sand pillows along the coastal belt to avert rough sea waves
from eroding the land, have been carried out for more than 40 to
50 years.
</P>
<P>
The Coast Conservation Development of Sri Lanka has spent more
than 74 million U.S. dollars so far, which is exactly the amount
of the money the ministry has asked from the ADB to bring the
problem of sea erosion under control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
