<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Equities staged a recovery
though the volume remained low on the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE)
market during the past week in the wake of hectic purchases by
foreign funds and domestic institutions.
</P>
<P>
The sensitive index of the BSE, which moved in a narrow range
in the early days of the week, showed a net gain of 66.72 points
closing the week at 2,849.82 as against last weekend's close of
2,783.1.
</P>
<P>
The national index also gained 24.16 points from the previous
weekend's close of 1,242.33. The BSE-200 and U.S. dollar index
were quoted up at 294.1 and 115.1 compared with last weekend's
close of 289.03 and 113.17 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The volume of business on the BSE, however, was very low at
45.88 billion rupees (1.11 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The volume continued to be low due to disinterest by investors,
who considered the present prevailing political situation
unfavorable for fresh investments in the stocks, traders said.
