<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Exports of Red Beans up Dramatically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- China's red bean exporters are
turning in an especially stellar performance this year although
their major traditional buyers, Japan and the Republic of Korea,
have been heavily hit by the Asian financial turmoil, today's
Business Weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the General Administration of
Customs, China's red bean exports amounted to 34,800 tons during
the first nine months, surging 60 percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Turnover reached 16.5 million U.S. dollars, a 52 percent
increase from last year.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian financial crisis has not exerted much negative
influence on China's red bean exports," an official with the China
Chamber of Commerce for Imports and Exports of Foodstuffs, Native
Produce and Animal By-products was cited as saying.
</P>
<P>
The amount of Chinese red beans exported to Japan soared 113
percent from last year to hit 16,200 tons by the end of September,
with turnover rising about 100 percent to 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan used to depend completely on China to satisfy its large
demand-supply gap for red beans.
</P>
<P>
Although the Japanese Government has made efforts to reduce
this reliance, about 90 percent of Japanese red bean imports still
come from China.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Japan and the Republic of Korea each take 30 percent
of China's red bean exports, with Southeast Asian economies
absorbing the rest.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the strong growth of China's red bean
exports to the government's loosening of controls on red bean
export quotas early this year.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to ward off the impact of the crisis, the Chinese
government cancelled the export quota bidding mechanism for more
than 20 commodities, making them more accessible to exporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
