<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Promulgate Regulations on Prices of Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- China will soon promulgate
regulations on medicine prices to pave the way for reform of the
country's health-care system, Business Weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the regulations are aimed at
ensuring that major medicines will remain affordable to ordinary
Chinese people as government subsidies in health-care are
significantly slashed.
</P>
<P>
The new health care system aims to make individuals, work units
and the government jointly responsible for medical costs, instead
of the whole burden being shouldered by employees' work units.
</P>
<P>
The present medicine prices have been pushed up to high levels
by kickbacks, which are common practice throughout the health
sector.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the profit margins will be limited to within
five percent of the medicine's price set by wholesale and retail
to ensure that the prices should not be pushed up.
</P>
<P>
The government will reset prices for commonly used medicines
according to their current production and distribution costs. For
medicines whose prices are decided by producers themselves, the
government will put limits on profit ranges.
</P>
<P>
Importers of foreign medicines will have to report prices to
the pricing administrative organizations and get approval in
advance to redistribute and resell them.
</P>
<P>
Prices will be an important factor in decisions on import
licenses. If prices are found to be too high, the medicines may
not be imported into China, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will be imposed regardless of the ownership
structure of the medicine makers. Producers and trading firms
will suffer severe punishment, including stiff fines or even
closure, if they are caught not following the new rules on pricing.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations will allow bigger profit margins for
medicines that demand high technological inputs. This provision
aims to spur domestic medical manufacturers to raise investment in
new and high-tech medicines to increase their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Medicine imports hit 500 million U.S. dollars in China in 1995,
compared to only 30 million U.S. dollars in the 1970s. And there
are 1,500 overseas-financed businesses in medicine-making industry
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian Plane Makes Emergency Landing in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A Hungarian plane made an
emergency landing in Turkey after a drunk passenger attacked the
crew and died on board the plane, the Hungarian news agency MTI
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency identified the Finnish passenger as Mikaeinar
Peterson, and said that he began to attack stewardesses
and passengers when the Bangkok to Budapest airliner was flying
over Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Crew members then tied him into his seat with the help of
passengers and a doctor traveling as a passenger gave him an
injection to calm him, according other news reports.
</P>
<P>
But in half an hour, the man became difficult in breathing and
died in the seat.
</P>
<P>
The pilots asked Istanbul airport for permission for an
emergency landing after the incident took place.
</P>
<P>
When the plane touched down, Peterson's body was taken to
hospital in Istanbul for determining the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
The plane was carrying 190 passengers and a crew of six.
</P>
<P>
The crew members and several passengers were asked to stay in
Turkey for investigation. Other passengers arrived in Budapest at
7:10 p.m., 13 hours late aboard the same plane, which was flew by
a separate crew, reports said. 
</P>
