<HEADLINE> Brazil to Invest 300 Million U.S. Dollars to Combat AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government will
invest 300 million U.S. dollars in the next four years in the
fight against AIDS, government sources said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry said that the Brazilian government will
contribute 135 million dollars of the total and the rest 165
million dollars will be financed by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Jose Serra will leave for Washington on
Tuesday, where he will sign an agreement on the issue with the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The government program aims to expand the supply of preventive
tools and the education for the control of AIDS, particularly
among women, young people, and people with lower income.
</P>
<P>
The first AIDS case in Brazil was registered in the 1970s.
AIDS cases have so far been reported in more than half of the
5,774 cities and towns in the country. 
</P>
