<HEADLINE> Myanmar Studies European Monetary Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is studying the
functions and new systems of European monetary organizations in
the wake of a plan of the 13-member European Monetary Union (EMU)
to launch euro bank notes soon.
</P>
<P>
A seminar on the EMU creating an entirely new global economic
system, jointly sponsored by the Central Bank of Myanmar and the
Dresdner Bank of Germany, was held here on Friday to study the
move.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister of Finance and Revenue U Khin Maung Thein
urged local bank officials participating in the seminar to use
their knowledge for improvement of their services.
</P>
<P>
Matters relating to the EMU were also discussed at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is a member of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
In October, the World Bank declared Myanmar ineligible for new
loans because it has not repaid the outstanding ones.
</P>
<P>
Regarding this, Myanmar responded by postponing the repayment
of loans to the World Bank until the latter resumes lending.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has suspended all loans to Myanmar since 1987,
charging that Myanmar is unwilling to modify the highly
distortional economic policies that the bank concludes have
created an environment in which external aid resources could not
be efficiently utilized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, although the impact of the Asian financial crisis on
 Myanmar has not been as serious as that on other Southeast Asian
nations, a further devaluation of the local currency has been
brought about after the introduction of the new 1,000-kyat bank
note last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
