<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerating Gold Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- China is breaking industrial
and regional restraints in gold production, a decades-old monopoly
by the state, today's Business Weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at achieving a sustainable growth of the
sector to meet the increasing demand for the precious metal on the
domestic market, Wang Dexue, director of the gold bureau with the
State Economic and Trade Commission, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
With constantly improving living standards, Chinese people are
buying more gold articles for decorative and investment
purposes. Demand reached 213.8 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
China ranks third in the world in gold sales, after the United
States and India. But per capita purchasing last year was only 0.2
grams on average, 1.3 grams less than the world average.
</P>
<P>
To tap the potential, the country has begun to transform the
industry into a market-oriented one, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Other industrial sectors can explore gold resources after
gaining approval from the authorities concerned.
</P>
<P>
Provinces with capital in hand can join in gold mining programs
in other provinces that have gold resources but lack funds.
</P>
<P>
The central government is also encouraging cooperation and
exchange in capital and technology with overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Yet due to declining gold prices and the government's
permission for foreign companies to explore only low-quality
mines, cooperation in the industry worldwide is at a low ebb.
</P>
<P>
However, Liu Shan'en, deputy director of the Gold Economic
Development Research Center, said that China had to depend largely
on its own resources to restructure the gold industry, and that he
was optimistic about the country's ability to realize successful
transition of it.
</P>
<P>
China's gold output reached 139.3 tons during the first ten
months of this year, up 18.4 percent from the same period of last
year. Total output this year is expected to reach 170 tons,
compared with last year's record high of 166.3 tons.
</P>
<P>
China's gold industry has grown for 12 consecutive years, with
annual average growth of ten percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
