<HEADLINE> Man Makes Fishbone Pictures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Gang, who lives in the
city of Tianjin, has made over 150 pictures using the bones of
more than 50 different types of freshwater and saltwater fish
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai office of the Guiness Book of World Records has
certified his fishbone pictures.
</P>
<P>
Zhao has produced the 4.5-meter-long "One Hundred Fish" picture
and the 0.5-centimeter-long seabed scene using fish bones.
</P>
<P>
Fish bones are superior to the bones of other animals, Zhao
explains, and almost every piece is usable. He uses the carp, with
its 360 bones, as an example. More than 50 of the bones are in
strange shapes and Zhao uses his imagination when looking at bones.
</P>
<P>
Gills can be used as coconut and pine trees, scales as grapes
and plum blossoms and Zhao can produce images of bamboo, peacock
feathers, camels, gourds, birds, and orchids.
</P>
<P>
Zhao was encouraged to make pictures as a boy. His interest in
fish bone shapes led to that of butterflies, cattle, and
elephants, all of this encouraged by his family.
</P>
<P>
Zhao has also found ways to remove the fat from the bones to
preserve them so that a fishbone picture can last for least 10
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
