<HEADLINE> EU to Discuss European Solution to Ocalan Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini said European Union (EU) foreign ministers will study on
Monday the feasibility of dealing with the case of Ocalan on a
European level.
</P>
<P>
Dini told reporters Saturday in Reggio Emilia, northern Italy,
that the monthly meeting of the EU's 15 ministers in Brussels
would provide an opportunity for "seeing whether a European
solution for trying Ocalan has the necessary backing."
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Ocalan, leader of the outlawed Kurdistan Workers'
Party fighting for Kurdish autonomy in southeast Turkey, was
detained in Rome on November 12 and is now under house arrest in
Rome on the basis of a German arrest warrant, although Germany has
said that it would not request his extradition.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan is Turkey's most wanted man, held responsible by the
Turkish government for thousands of deaths in his party's
14-year-old struggle for autonomy.
</P>
<P>
But an Italian court rejected Turkish demands for Ocalan's
extradition, sparking a dramatic deterioration in relations
between Rome and Ankara.
</P>
<P>
A German and Italian backed proposal that Ocalan be tried in an
international court has been flatly rejected by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Dini tried to ease tensions by saying that it was "important to
obtain Turkey's approval for legal proceedings to take place
outside those countries (Germany and Turkey)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
