<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Editor's Note: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The following is the third in a series of articles on the
fast-changing life and culture of the Zhuang, Miao, Yao, Shui, and
seven other ethnic groups in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
in southern China. They are being prepared by Xinhua reporters to
mark Guangxi's 40th anniversary on December 11.
</P>
<P>
 Guangxi Ethnic Group Series:
</P>
<P>
Land Policy Harmonizes the Yao with Other Ethnic Groups (1)
</P>
<P>
NANNING, December 6 (Xinhua) -- Dayao Mountain in the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region is where most Yao people live in compact
communities. This region was once a battleground where the Yao,
Zhuang and Han ethnic groups fought over rights to the land.
</P>
<P>
The bloodiest fighting occured in 1884 when Hans who died in
battle were buried on a hill which came to be known as The Tomb of
Han.
</P>
<P>
A primary school is now on this site where the children of many
ethnic groups study and play together. Li Zhaojun, director of the
Ethnic Affairs Bureau of Jinxiu County, said there have been no
conflicts between ethnic groups in Dayao since the founding of new
China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yulian, professor at the Central Ethnic Minorities
University, said that disputes over land was the major cause of
clashes among ethnic groups and among the Yao people themselves,
but the land policy of the Chinese government has brought a stable
and long-lasting peace to Dayao.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has 860,000 Yao people, divided into five branches, who
inter-marry and live together in harmony.
</P>
<P>
Farming land belongs to the collective and all farmers,
irrespective of their ethnic background, enjoys equal right. Farm
fields began to be distributed to each family for farming at the
start of rural reform in 1978, greatly heightening Yao's
enthusiasm for rural production. They then planted trees,
medicinal herbs and other cash crops in the previously barren
hills, which has brought them considerable economic returns.
</P>
<P>
The aniseed produced in Jinxiu county is exported to Hong Kong,
Japan and France and has earned 30 million yuan for local
farmers. By the end of last year, all the people in Jinxiu had
sufficient food and clothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Ethnic Group Series: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the people in Dayao became better off, relations between
ethnic groups grew more harmonious, and the tradition of not
marrying outside of one's own people was also abandoned.
</P>
<P>
Chen Song, a young Zhuang man, married into a Yao village and
led the village down the road to prosperity. The per capita annual
income of this village has been increased to 6,000 yuan, and this
year, Chen was reelected head of the village committee.
</P>
<P>
Professor Liu, a native of Dayao, said that land reform put all
the ethnic groups on an equal footing, and the household
responsibility contract system solved the problem of food and
clothing, adding that the common prosperity of all ethnic groups
brought real equality and unity to Dayao.
</P>
<P>
A new round of land contract is now underway in Dayao, and the
thirty-year land contracts enable farmers to set long-term goals
for their farming. To date, 80 percent of the farmers here have
signed such contracts.
</P>
<P>
One villager said he worried about changes in state policy in
the past, but now, with his contract in hand, he no longer needs
fear that the state might take back the use right of his farmland,
and this makes him a better farmer, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
