<DOCNO> XIE19981206.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Industries Grow Fast for Two Decades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 6 (Xinhua) -- The past two decades have seen
most fast development ever in the manufacturing sector of
Shanghai, China's largest industrial and commercial city.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that since 1978, Shanghai's industrial
output value has increased at an average rate of 10.6 percent a
year, reaching 560.6 billion yuan in 1997, 6.8 times that of 1978,
and payment to the state has continued to rise at an average rate
of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dramatic changes have taken place in the product mix of local
industries as well. As a result, sophisticate goods such as
integrated circuits, color TVs, and automotives and fax machines
have replaced the city's former leading products including
bicycles, radios, electric fans and sewing machines.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute this progress to the ongoing economic
restructuring and the reform of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old reform and opening drive have made local
industries an increasingly attractive sector for private and
overseas investors, who now contribute 53.4 percent to the city's
industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, Shanghai has readjusted the local
industrial structure by placing light industry on the same footing
with heavy industry, while promoting the hi-tech sector, which now
generates some 16 percent of the city's total industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the manufacturing sector has taken steps to
explore international markets to a greater extent, and last year
Shanghai's exports surpassed 100 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
