<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Positive Cases in Pakistan Reach 80,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 50,000 to 80,000
HIV infected cases have been reported in Pakistan which calls for
prompt and stringent steps at grassroots level to contain the
virus from further spreading.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the local media Saturday, Barjees Mazhar Qazi,
National Aids Program manager, said AIDS epidemic casts adverse
impacts on social and economic fabric of any community.
</P>
<P>
He said the HIV virus is a very deceptive one which even could
not be detected in many cases in five to 10 years even after
proper tests and investigations.
</P>
<P>
Qazi maintained that about 30 million people in the world today
are with HIV infection and one-third of them are young people aged
10 to 24.
</P>
<P>
He said that every day about 7,000 young people worldwide
acquire the virus. This means that around 2.6 million persons
become infected a year among young people, including 1.7 million
in Africa and 700,000 in Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
He said young people account for at least 50 percent of all
those who become infected after infancy and in some countries the
figure exceeds 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Qazi asked Pakistanis to adhere to religious values and stick
to their life partners and avoid "unethical acts." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
