<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Closer Ties with Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel on Saturday expressed the hope that the ongoing visit by
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to Turkey will help promote
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"We held the talks in a sincere and friendly atmosphere, "
Demirel told reporters after meeting with Mubarak, who arrived
here at noon for a two-day tour.
</P>
<P>
"There are strong bases in the relations between Turkey and
Egypt and there is no any problem existing between the two
countries," added Demirel.
</P>
<P>
In his part, Mubarak said "we hope Turkey will develop strong,
constructive and productive relations with Egypt and other Arab
countries."
</P>
<P>
He said it is possible for Turkey and Egypt to exert mutual
efforts in strengthening bilateral political ties. He added Cairo
has decided to carry on regular consultations with Turkey in a bid
to further their existing ties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the Turkish-Israeli relations, Demirel stressed
that the existing ties will not target any third country.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly growing Turkish-Israeli military and defense
cooperation has drawn harsh criticism from Muslim world and
Arab countries who fear it will change the region's balance
of power.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have signed a series of military and defense
accords which lay down that the two countries carry out joint air
forces training and that Israel helps Turkey upgrade its aged
fighters and tanks.
</P>
<P>
The naval forces of Israel, Turkey and the United States
launched joint exercises in the international waters of the
eastern Mediterranean last January, prompting strong protests
from Iran and Arab countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
