<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fischer: No E.U. Enlargement Timetable Till Late 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union cannot issue a
timetable for taking in European states until late 1999, said
German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer in an interview to be
published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"This must really then offer a concrete and not a visionary
(membership) date," Fischer said in a Welt am Sonntag newspaper
interview made available in advance.
</P>
<P>
Fischer's remarks illustrate the deep contrast between
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's new government and former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl who had predicted Poland could become a
European Union (E.U.) member in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the chances for taking in new states in 2000,
Fischer replied: "Nobody believes that any more."
</P>
<P>
There would only be light at the end of the tunnel in
enlargement talks in late 1999, he said, adding this was the
earliest date for any E.U. expansion timetable.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the 15-nation E.U. will announce when it plans to take in
East European members over 10 years after the Berlin Wall's
collapse. In contrast, the NATO alliance will admit its first new
post-Cold War members next year: Poland, the Czech Republic and
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Looking toward next week's Vienna summit of E.U. leaders,
Fischer warned that Bonn would not pay the bills for planned
reform of the bloc prior to enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Germany wants its annual net payments to the E.U. of 22 billion
marks (13 billion dollars) to be cut as part of Union budget
reform under the Agenda 2000 package which will also seek to
revamp farm subsidy spending and infrastructure aid to the E.U.'s
poorer regions.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder says he hopes to complete the Agenda 2000 by next
March while Germany holds the rotating E.U. presidency during the
first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We want this success but not at any price. None of our
European partners should believe they can just lean back because
the German government needs a success on domestic policy grounds,"
said Fischer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
